WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.150 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:24.310
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:
Good afternoon and welcome

00:00:24.310 --> 00:00:25.750
to the Library of Congress.

00:00:25.750 --> 00:00:28.930
My name is Talia Guzman-Gonzalez
and I am a reference librarian

00:00:28.930 --> 00:00:31.900
and Luso-Brazilian specialist
in the Hispanic Division.

00:00:31.900 --> 00:00:35.270
It is my great pleasure to
have you all here to talk

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:38.300
about Exile, Diaspora,
and Return:

00:00:38.300 --> 00:00:40.760
Changing Cultural Landscapes
in Argentina, Chile,

00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:43.050
Uruguay, and Paraguay.

00:00:43.050 --> 00:00:49.620
A team research project by
Luis Roniger, Leonardo Senkman,

00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:52.890
Saúl Sosnowski, and
Mario Sznajder.

00:00:52.890 --> 00:00:56.500
Today we have with us two
of the authors of the book,

00:00:56.500 --> 00:01:00.020
two of the team members, Luis
and Saúl, who will be talking

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:02.840
with Professor Juan
Uriagereka from the Department

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:05.820
of Linguistics and
Professor Ernesto Calvo

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:08.330
from the Department of
Government and Politics,

00:01:08.330 --> 00:01:11.310
both at the University
of Maryland College Park.

00:01:11.310 --> 00:01:15.110
I'm going to briefly introduce
Professors Roniger and Sosnowski

00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:19.250
and then I'm going to pass
the microphone to Saúl

00:01:19.250 --> 00:01:22.140
who will be the emcee
for the event.

00:01:22.140 --> 00:01:23.920
Luis Roniger is Reynolds
Professor

00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:27.120
of Latin American Studies
at Wake Forest University.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:30.580
He is a comparative political
sociologist and his work focuses

00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:32.650
on the interface
between politics,

00:01:32.650 --> 00:01:35.010
society, and public culture.

00:01:35.010 --> 00:01:37.720
He has published numerous
journal articles and books

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:40.980
on a vast range of topics
including human rights,

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:45.670
transitional politics, exile
and democracy in Latin America.

00:01:45.670 --> 00:01:47.840
Professor Roniger is the author

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:50.790
of "Destierro y exilio
en America Latina,

00:01:50.790 --> 00:01:53.540
Nuevos estudios y avances
teoricos" published

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:57.530
by the University of
Buenos Aires in 2014,

00:01:57.530 --> 00:02:00.260
and "Tres estudios sobre el
exilio: Condicion humana,

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:03.350
experiencia historica y
significacion politica",

00:02:03.350 --> 00:02:09.700
co-author with Arturo Aguirre
and Antolin Sanchez in 2014 too,

00:02:09.700 --> 00:02:11.300
and also "Transnational Politics

00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:15.510
in Central America"
published in 2011.

00:02:15.510 --> 00:02:17.110
Saúl Sosnowski is
currently professor

00:02:17.110 --> 00:02:19.490
of Latin American Literature
and Culture at the University

00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:23.560
of Maryland in College Park
besides having held many other

00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:25.890
administrative positions
such as Director

00:02:25.890 --> 00:02:31.120
of the Latin American Studies
Center which he founded in 1989.

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:34.420
Professor Sosnowski has been
the force we had many important

00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:38.560
initiatives in academic projects
such as a decade-long series

00:02:38.560 --> 00:02:42.080
of international conferences,
"The Repression of Culture

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:45.650
and its Reconstruction
in the Southern Cone".

00:02:45.650 --> 00:02:47.190
He is the founder and editor

00:02:47.190 --> 00:02:50.190
of the literary journal
Hispania, currently--

00:02:50.190 --> 00:02:51.490
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: Hispamerica.

00:02:51.490 --> 00:02:52.790
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:
Hispamerica, sorry.

00:02:52.790 --> 00:02:55.430
Yeah. Currently in what,

00:02:55.430 --> 00:02:58.440
currently in what
issue, what-- Saúl?

00:02:58.440 --> 00:02:59.780
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: 47th year.

00:02:59.780 --> 00:03:01.080
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:
47th year.

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:02.380
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: Yeah.

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:03.680
&gt;&gt; Talia Guzman-Gonzalez:
Amazing.

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:06.150
And I lost where I was.

00:03:06.150 --> 00:03:08.370
Thank you.

00:03:08.370 --> 00:03:11.360
His work centers on issues
of civic education, democracy

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:13.920
and conflict management
and cultural politics

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:15.880
with the focus on Latin America.

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:19.450
He is the author of "Julio
Cortaza: una busqueda mitica",

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:22.380
"Borges y la Cabala:
la busqueda del Verbo",

00:03:22.380 --> 00:03:26.770
currently in its third edition
and translated into Portuguese

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:30.810
and German, and "La orilla
imminente: escritores judios-

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:35.270
argentinos, Fascismo y nazismo
en las letras argentinas"

00:03:35.270 --> 00:03:37.710
with Leonardo Senkman,

00:03:37.710 --> 00:03:40.100
and "Cartografia de las
letras hispanoamericanas:

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:41.970
tejidos de la memoria".

00:03:41.970 --> 00:03:44.420
Please join me in welcoming
our distinguished guests

00:03:44.420 --> 00:03:46.510
to the Library of Congress.

00:03:46.510 --> 00:03:51.030
[ Applause ]

00:03:51.030 --> 00:03:52.380
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski:
Thank you, Talia.

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:54.800
And through you I would also
like to thank Georgia Durham

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:59.580
for the arrangements and for
the invitation to be able

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:03.540
to present Exile,
Diaspora, and Return:

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:06.620
Changing Cultural Landscapes
in Argentina, Chile, Paraguay,

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:12.010
and Uruguay, a book that was
produced by four colleagues.

00:04:12.010 --> 00:04:15.400
I was going to say quatro
amigos, then the reference is

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:18.810
to tres amigos and we are in the
[inaudible] pick for two room

00:04:18.810 --> 00:04:22.640
and this is leading
us someplace else.

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:30.920
And the four of us, Luis
Roniger, a sociologist,

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:33.790
Mario Sznajder, a
political scientist,

00:04:33.790 --> 00:04:37.500
Leonardo Senkman a historian,
and I from the literary side,

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:42.240
have been working on
these kinds of issues

00:04:42.240 --> 00:04:44.060
from different vantage points

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:47.060
and different perspectives
for quite a while.

00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:53.590
And we decided at some point
that it would be a good idea

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:56.810
to approach a neglected area,

00:04:56.810 --> 00:04:59.530
what we consider the
neglected area of research

00:04:59.530 --> 00:05:03.560
about which my colleagues will
be speaking a little later.

00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:06.590
So the first meeting took
place as many meetings

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:11.880
of this sort take place
in Jerusalem and it--

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:14.330
or the Hebrew University
of Jerusalem

00:05:14.330 --> 00:05:16.880
on the Mount Scopus Campus.

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:23.350
And once we decided that we were
going to engage in this product,

00:05:23.350 --> 00:05:27.580
in this project that
turned out to be a product,

00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:32.470
we held meetings in different
parts of Latin America as well

00:05:32.470 --> 00:05:37.950
as here and more
than once in Israel.

00:05:37.950 --> 00:05:41.400
And this was due to the
fact that we were very lucky

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:45.440
to obtain the support from the
Binational Science Foundation

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:50.400
Israel to US that allowed us
to carry out this research

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:56.250
which mandated several trips in
order to interview a whole array

00:05:56.250 --> 00:06:00.780
of people in each of
the four countries,

00:06:00.780 --> 00:06:04.540
and more about that
a little later.

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:09.100
The transition to democracy
in each case was subject

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:13.240
to very radically different
approaches and conditions

00:06:13.240 --> 00:06:17.500
which in turn conditioned and
affected the process of return,

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:21.130
the policies to promote
such a return and the impact

00:06:21.130 --> 00:06:25.690
that returnees have had on
the respective countries.

00:06:25.690 --> 00:06:29.860
And this is a subject that
I'm sure will be touched upon

00:06:29.860 --> 00:06:32.130
by our colleagues.

00:06:32.130 --> 00:06:36.470
I think it is worth
noting that though none

00:06:36.470 --> 00:06:41.360
of the four authors currently
live in our birthplace,

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:43.490
three of us are from Argentina

00:06:43.490 --> 00:06:47.640
and even the Chilean among
us was born in Buenos Aires

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:49.520
but he opted for
becoming a Chilean,

00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:53.440
a common mistake by some people.

00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:57.860
One of our defining
identities is clearly anchored

00:06:57.860 --> 00:06:59.470
in the region.

00:06:59.470 --> 00:07:02.330
Objective analysis in carrying

00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:05.830
out research has been
a guiding principle,

00:07:05.830 --> 00:07:09.360
but so I sense it's a sense
of commitment that each one

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:12.440
of us has to the region, sort

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:17.650
of a necessary unavoidable
commitment to both memory

00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:20.640
and to the unfolding present.

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:25.120
I'm very grateful to two of my
colleagues from the University

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:31.630
of Maryland who have agreed to
speak about some of the issues

00:07:31.630 --> 00:07:35.100
that are addressed in the
book, maybe about the book too,

00:07:35.100 --> 00:07:40.900
but we'll find out shortly since
both of them have been very,

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:44.180
very active in related issues.

00:07:44.180 --> 00:07:46.240
Ernesto Calvo who holds a PhD

00:07:46.240 --> 00:07:50.160
from Northwestern University is
a professor and associate chair

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:52.330
in the Department of
Government and Politics

00:07:52.330 --> 00:07:54.530
at the University of Maryland.

00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:57.620
His research on political
representation, elections

00:07:57.620 --> 00:08:01.480
and congresses has
received numerous awards.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:05.930
He is the author of "Legislator
Success in Fragmented Congresses

00:08:05.930 --> 00:08:07.400
in Argentina" published

00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:10.690
by Cambridge University
Press in 2014.

00:08:10.690 --> 00:08:12.690
"La nueva politica de Partidos"

00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:16.580
by Prometeo years
before in 2005.

00:08:16.580 --> 00:08:19.650
And relatively-- recently

00:08:19.650 --> 00:08:25.360
"Anatomia Politica de Twitter en
Argentina: tuiteando #Nisman",

00:08:25.360 --> 00:08:29.300
a project that gathered
the attention of many

00:08:29.300 --> 00:08:33.310
of our graduate students
at College Park.

00:08:33.310 --> 00:08:36.320
He's currently conducting
research and patronage networks,

00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:40.850
co-sponsorship networks
and representation.

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:43.310
Ernesto Calvo will
be going first.

00:08:43.310 --> 00:08:46.390
But in order to make it
a smoother transition,

00:08:46.390 --> 00:08:52.370
let me introduce already
Juan Uriagereka who says

00:08:52.370 --> 00:08:53.670
that whatever I'm going

00:08:53.670 --> 00:08:56.910
to be telling you right now
really does not represent him.

00:08:56.910 --> 00:08:58.670
And in a way it's sort of true

00:08:58.670 --> 00:09:01.840
because he's a lot more
done what I'm going

00:09:01.840 --> 00:09:03.140
to be reading to you.

00:09:03.140 --> 00:09:06.760
But that is the case of
our other friends also.

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:09.750
He is a linguist who has
joined the University

00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:11.660
of Maryland in 1989.

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:15.930
I must say that when he
joined Maryland, he also came

00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:18.970
in a joint appointment with
Spanish and Portuguese.

00:09:18.970 --> 00:09:21.780
Later he drifted
towards linguistic,

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:24.770
but that mistake will be
remedied effective this coming

00:09:24.770 --> 00:09:29.350
fall when he will become part
of the Department of Spanish

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:33.150
and Portuguese while
maintaining his affiliation

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:34.450
with linguistics.

00:09:34.450 --> 00:09:36.120
He has published a dozen books

00:09:36.120 --> 00:09:38.720
on language structure
including two textbooks,

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:41.070
"The Minimalist Program"
and its precursors,

00:09:41.070 --> 00:09:44.030
as well as many articles
and chapters.

00:09:44.030 --> 00:09:48.150
He is a founding member of
the Linguistics Department.

00:09:48.150 --> 00:09:51.540
And in his capacity as
Associate Provost for Faculty,

00:09:51.540 --> 00:09:54.810
a post he held for quite a few
years, he lead the approval

00:09:54.810 --> 00:09:57.580
and promotion of
family-friendly policies,

00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:01.230
regularizing the status of
professional track faculty,

00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:02.970
organizing leadership forums

00:10:02.970 --> 00:10:05.990
and updating promotion
and tenure policies.

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:08.960
His current book
projects include the books

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:13.280
"Biolinguistic Investigations on
the Formal Language Hierarchy",

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:16.880
a monograph in progress and
structure with Howard Lasnik,

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:20.760
and a multidisciplinary project
to formulate language structures

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:25.330
as linear operators of the sort
employed in machine learning.

00:10:25.330 --> 00:10:28.210
Having said that, which
sounds very technical,

00:10:28.210 --> 00:10:31.010
the most important part is
that when he came to Maryland,

00:10:31.010 --> 00:10:34.520
he said it works with
both sides of his brain.

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:37.780
And he is a fiction writer.

00:10:37.780 --> 00:10:42.840
And not just-- and we have a
few things cooking along the way

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:46.130
that, well, maybe a little
presentation here one day.

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:48.450
We'll see.

00:10:48.450 --> 00:10:52.370
Gentlemen, thank you first of
all for agreeing to be here

00:10:52.370 --> 00:10:55.300
and the floor is yours, Ernesto.

00:10:56.510 --> 00:11:04.260
[ Applause ]

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:05.560
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo: So first,

00:11:05.560 --> 00:11:07.760
thank you so much
for the invitation.

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:12.510
And I love the book, so
it's a nice book to present.

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:16.580
I do have to say that it's a
bit of a self-serving likeness

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:20.060
of the book because there's
a lot of things that happened

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:21.880
in the book and there are a
lot of things that are related

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:24.140
that actually go to
my personal life.

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:29.630
So let me start by pointing to a
couple of anecdotes that I think

00:11:29.630 --> 00:11:32.400
that highlight I think
what's a true contribution

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:34.410
at least for me of the book.

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:39.440
So we're having common
Lazaro Cardenas,

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:40.740
[inaudible], the Dow Jones, MTV.

00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:44.240
So let me start with a story.

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:48.650
So when-- in 1976 my family
went to Mexico on exile.

00:11:48.650 --> 00:11:52.730
My mother is [inaudible] and
pretty much the entire side

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:57.750
of my family went to either
Mexico, Spain or Venezuela.

00:11:57.750 --> 00:12:00.900
So, most of the exile community
which is actually told here,

00:12:00.900 --> 00:12:04.150
you know, with the kids,
they put kids in communities

00:12:04.150 --> 00:12:06.770
and we were connected to
each other, we form networks.

00:12:06.770 --> 00:12:08.070
The kind of networks that are--

00:12:08.070 --> 00:12:09.370
we're able to describe
in the book

00:12:09.370 --> 00:12:10.920
that have been persisting
for, you know,

00:12:10.920 --> 00:12:12.220
40 years at this point.

00:12:12.220 --> 00:12:15.070
So when a lot of us
went to one school

00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:16.370
that was called [inaudible].

00:12:16.370 --> 00:12:17.770
Maybe some of you,
if you're connected

00:12:17.770 --> 00:12:21.280
to the Afghan-Mex
committee heard about it.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:25.320
And in the [inaudible] we would
have practices that we would go

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:26.840
to the countryside in Mexico.

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:28.710
The first one that
we went was to do--

00:12:28.710 --> 00:12:32.020
to analyze wood production
in Mexico in Michoacán.

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:33.640
At the time the governor

00:12:33.640 --> 00:12:35.570
of Michoacán was
Cuauhtémoc Cárdenas.

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:38.250
And his son, Lazaro Cardenas
was actually a classmate

00:12:38.250 --> 00:12:39.550
of my brother.

00:12:39.550 --> 00:12:40.850
And because he was the
son of the governor,

00:12:40.850 --> 00:12:44.890
he organized the meeting so
that we could put our tents

00:12:44.890 --> 00:12:46.820
in the government
house the first day

00:12:46.820 --> 00:12:48.970
because then we would
go to the area

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:50.840
that wood was being produced.

00:12:50.840 --> 00:12:53.070
So the first night when we
were in the government mansion,

00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:55.220
outside in the gardeners
with our tents,

00:12:55.220 --> 00:12:57.640
we start to hear
some odd noises.

00:12:57.640 --> 00:12:59.910
So we come out, several
of us, and start to hear

00:12:59.910 --> 00:13:03.050
that something was
going on in the tent.

00:13:03.050 --> 00:13:07.450
And tent was Lazaro Cardenas
with one of our teachers,

00:13:07.450 --> 00:13:10.030
which was also a
refugee from Uruguay.

00:13:10.030 --> 00:13:13.570
And outside of the tent was,
you know a lot my friends

00:13:13.570 --> 00:13:18.060
that was the son of Pepe Perez
[assumed spelling] which is one

00:13:18.060 --> 00:13:19.640
of the historians at the time,

00:13:19.640 --> 00:13:21.090
historians for most
historians was the--

00:13:21.090 --> 00:13:23.750
the director of the
museum archeology

00:13:23.750 --> 00:13:28.030
and he was [inaudible] which was
the stepson of [inaudible] also

00:13:28.030 --> 00:13:31.370
in the book which later wrote
the discourse of [inaudible]

00:13:31.370 --> 00:13:32.900
and then was [inaudible].

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:39.290
So it was about twelve of
us from Chile, from Uruguay,

00:13:39.290 --> 00:13:42.660
from Argentina because a lot
of the community in exile puts

00:13:42.660 --> 00:13:44.330
in kids in sort of
the same school.

00:13:44.330 --> 00:13:46.720
And it was a school on the
left political spectrum.

00:13:46.720 --> 00:13:48.650
We would organize
politically there.

00:13:48.650 --> 00:13:50.710
And we have formed strong
bonds and you would see

00:13:50.710 --> 00:13:52.550
that through layers
of generations

00:13:52.550 --> 00:13:54.940
that would call our [inaudible]
and we would be the, you know,

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:57.910
sons and daughters of the
people who went in exile.

00:13:57.910 --> 00:13:59.530
So the book is really good.

00:13:59.530 --> 00:14:00.830
I'm describing something

00:14:00.830 --> 00:14:02.870
that generally has not been
well portrayed which is

00:14:02.870 --> 00:14:07.080
that exiles are of very
different kinds and they're--

00:14:07.080 --> 00:14:08.890
the sort of terror
and destruction

00:14:08.890 --> 00:14:13.000
that triggers the situation
exile does not necessarily

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.290
continues in the
same way, you know.

00:14:16.290 --> 00:14:19.350
In a way eventually exile
for many other people

00:14:19.350 --> 00:14:22.340
that I know became
a source of pride,

00:14:22.340 --> 00:14:24.080
a source of community building.

00:14:24.080 --> 00:14:25.810
And most of us remain connected.

00:14:25.810 --> 00:14:28.850
So when there earthquake
hit Mexico last year,

00:14:28.850 --> 00:14:31.430
we were calling all of
our friends in Mexico.

00:14:31.430 --> 00:14:35.370
And when one of our classmates
was kidnapped by the--

00:14:35.370 --> 00:14:39.320
by Pinochet in 1997, we were
demonstrating in Argentina.

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:40.790
We were demonstrating in Chile.

00:14:40.790 --> 00:14:42.740
We were demonstrating
in Mexico and Uruguay.

00:14:42.740 --> 00:14:44.080
So this community started

00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:47.800
to produce very significant
networks

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:50.280
that connected our countries
and that remains the case.

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:53.090
We have, you know, friends that
are musicians that are playing

00:14:53.090 --> 00:14:56.010
in Mexico and some of them
are actually faculty here

00:14:56.010 --> 00:14:58.690
in California, in MIT,
some of them-- my friends.

00:14:58.690 --> 00:14:59.990
That's not me.

00:14:59.990 --> 00:15:02.700
And so, then--

00:15:02.700 --> 00:15:04.480
&gt;&gt; Which I turned it off.

00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:06.540
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo: Santiago Perez
I was saying for example ended

00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:11.480
up being the director of
Dow Jones for Latin America,

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:12.790
[inaudible] ended
up in MTV as a--

00:15:12.790 --> 00:15:17.740
one of the creatives of
MIT-- MTV doing publicity.

00:15:17.740 --> 00:15:20.850
So every one of those remained
connected to the network

00:15:20.850 --> 00:15:23.470
and we have our own Facebook
page which is [inaudible]

00:15:23.470 --> 00:15:28.890
where we connect and track
each other's history.

00:15:28.890 --> 00:15:33.400
The source and pride and glory
of the school is Chivo Lubezki

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:35.130
which is, you know, the one

00:15:35.130 --> 00:15:38.240
that won three Oscars
for cinematography.

00:15:38.240 --> 00:15:40.940
That was actually was a Mexican.

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:43.660
So and-- so one of
the interesting things

00:15:43.660 --> 00:15:47.550
about the book is it starts
by narrating exile not just

00:15:47.550 --> 00:15:53.960
as a source of a terror, demise,
death, sort of their picture

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:55.830
that you have from there
Nacional Buenos Aires

00:15:55.830 --> 00:15:57.900
where a lot of you have
seen these pictures,

00:15:57.900 --> 00:15:59.200
a very classic picture
of [inaudible],

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:03.400
a picture of the class of
1975 in the Buenos Aires,

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:06.690
most of which ended
up in exile or death.

00:16:06.690 --> 00:16:09.220
So that's a picture that most

00:16:09.220 --> 00:16:12.570
of the narratives of
exiles begin with.

00:16:12.570 --> 00:16:14.780
But what they don't say
is what happen afterwards,

00:16:14.780 --> 00:16:17.560
which is how these
communities start to build roots

00:16:17.560 --> 00:16:19.770
and they start to
become very transnational

00:16:19.770 --> 00:16:26.070
and start operating a very large
number of countries socially,

00:16:26.070 --> 00:16:29.890
culturally, politically, and
start to engage in activities

00:16:29.890 --> 00:16:33.020
that will signify exile
and turn it into something

00:16:33.020 --> 00:16:36.140
that is pretty different.

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:39.640
So the book, what it does

00:16:39.640 --> 00:16:43.830
that I think is wonderful is
rebuilding those later networks.

00:16:43.830 --> 00:16:47.430
OK. How these people that
were on exile are reabsorbed,

00:16:47.430 --> 00:16:52.950
are reintegrated, how two things
are at the core of the community

00:16:52.950 --> 00:16:54.810
in exile that is returning?

00:16:54.810 --> 00:16:58.110
One, they come back
with political capital,

00:16:58.110 --> 00:17:00.310
with social capital,
with cultural capital

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:02.710
that allows them
to give a narrative

00:17:02.710 --> 00:17:05.570
about both the dictatorship,
exile.

00:17:05.570 --> 00:17:08.380
The other one is that
it produces a network

00:17:08.380 --> 00:17:11.400
that overlays the network
in Latin America where all

00:17:11.400 --> 00:17:14.340
of Latin America is
touched by notes.

00:17:14.340 --> 00:17:17.390
So all of us have networks
in the other countries

00:17:17.390 --> 00:17:23.710
and are connected with
the Onam in Mexico

00:17:23.710 --> 00:17:27.780
or with the [inaudible] in
Mexico, FPB, the [inaudible].

00:17:27.780 --> 00:17:30.550
You know, all the different
institutions have actually

00:17:30.550 --> 00:17:31.950
members of exile.

00:17:31.950 --> 00:17:34.360
And it's not just the Argentina
exiles, the Argentina exiles,

00:17:34.360 --> 00:17:36.590
the Uruguayan exiles,
the Chilean exile.

00:17:36.590 --> 00:17:37.970
Twenty out of 22 countries

00:17:37.970 --> 00:17:40.190
of Latin America had
authoritarian regimes

00:17:40.190 --> 00:17:41.750
when we moved to Mexico.

00:17:41.750 --> 00:17:43.450
And Mexico was a big hub.

00:17:43.450 --> 00:17:44.750
Most of those countries

00:17:44.750 --> 00:17:47.690
that were authoritarians
produced communities that left

00:17:47.690 --> 00:17:52.550
to Italy as they described, to
Venezuela, to Spain, to France.

00:17:52.550 --> 00:17:54.180
And all of us remain connected

00:17:54.180 --> 00:17:57.040
because it was not different
families to different places.

00:17:57.040 --> 00:17:59.430
Oftentimes, we actually
have members in, you know,

00:17:59.430 --> 00:18:00.760
each one of those places.

00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:02.800
So as I was saying, you know,
my family goes in exile.

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:04.100
We went to Mexico.

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:05.630
One of my uncles
went to Venezuela,

00:18:05.630 --> 00:18:07.590
another one of my
uncles went to Spain.

00:18:07.590 --> 00:18:09.780
Then they moved to Spain,
the ones from Venezuela.

00:18:09.780 --> 00:18:15.090
Then all my cousins ended up
in the US doing academic work.

00:18:15.090 --> 00:18:18.020
And generally, I spend a couple
of months in a year in Argentina

00:18:18.020 --> 00:18:22.130
and maybe a month in the
other places in the region.

00:18:22.130 --> 00:18:26.870
And by rebuilding
these other structures

00:18:26.870 --> 00:18:29.000
that characterize
the exile, what--

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:36.220
what they do is to bring what
we actually remember from exile.

00:18:36.220 --> 00:18:40.240
Most of the pictures of exile
depict what happens with,

00:18:40.240 --> 00:18:42.710
you know, at the
time of departure.

00:18:42.710 --> 00:18:46.550
You know, the fact that my
father was in jail when he comes

00:18:46.550 --> 00:18:48.920
out and we're going to exile.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:52.330
He actually produces-- an entire
operation to try to cover us

00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:53.630
so that nothing would happen

00:18:53.630 --> 00:18:54.930
when we were exiting
the country.

00:18:54.930 --> 00:18:57.580
We arrived to Mexico and
everything is depleted.

00:18:57.580 --> 00:18:59.460
But over two, or
three, or four years,

00:18:59.460 --> 00:19:01.850
these networks actually
starts to build things

00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:04.720
that are extremely interesting,
and starts to build catalog

00:19:04.720 --> 00:19:09.600
that was impossible to being
thought about later on.

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:17.900
So in-- when in-- the
discussion, decision for example

00:19:17.900 --> 00:19:20.160
to go back to Argentina,
they hit right

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:21.460
on the nail of the segregation.

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:25.620
We had huge discussions
about where to go,

00:19:25.620 --> 00:19:27.970
when to go, what to go for.

00:19:27.970 --> 00:19:30.150
So for example three months
after democratization,

00:19:30.150 --> 00:19:31.450
I went back to Argentina

00:19:31.450 --> 00:19:33.980
but my parents were not
willing to do so yet.

00:19:33.980 --> 00:19:36.050
Not without knowing that
the situation was going

00:19:36.050 --> 00:19:37.350
to be politically stable.

00:19:37.350 --> 00:19:40.030
So I arrived to Argentina,
15-year-old,

00:19:40.030 --> 00:19:43.700
living on basically my community
or, you know, kids and parents

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:46.050
from exile that are
returning in different stages

00:19:46.050 --> 00:19:48.210
and that are producing
the same kind of--

00:19:48.210 --> 00:19:51.230
building bridges that we had
in Mexico when we arrived.

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:52.780
So the networks starts

00:19:52.780 --> 00:19:55.700
to be staged both going
forward and coming backward.

00:19:55.700 --> 00:19:57.930
And at the same time we have
some friends that had said

00:19:57.930 --> 00:19:59.750
to go back to Argentina
that once they're

00:19:59.750 --> 00:20:03.460
in Argentina realized that there
is no longer a political goal

00:20:03.460 --> 00:20:06.590
that they actually can sustain
or are willing to defend.

00:20:06.590 --> 00:20:09.170
So some of them go back to
Mexico or ended up in the US.

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:11.830
So you start to see these sort
of very different patterns

00:20:11.830 --> 00:20:14.640
of migration that carried and
networks have been created

00:20:14.640 --> 00:20:18.210
to a very large number
of places.

00:20:18.210 --> 00:20:21.850
So, each one of the chapters
is actually reconstructing part

00:20:21.850 --> 00:20:23.150
of those debates.

00:20:23.150 --> 00:20:26.400
Debates about should we
accept for example payment

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:30.280
for the hardships that
we face in an exile?

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:31.580
There was a huge discussion

00:20:31.580 --> 00:20:34.120
in the community whether
reparations should be accepted

00:20:34.120 --> 00:20:35.510
and we were very divided.

00:20:35.510 --> 00:20:37.570
We didn't want to
accept reparations

00:20:37.570 --> 00:20:38.980
but at the same time
other people wanted

00:20:38.980 --> 00:20:41.030
to accept reparations
and the decision

00:20:41.030 --> 00:20:43.540
to it was very personal, but
it was discussed collectively

00:20:43.540 --> 00:20:45.500
as our problem in our community.

00:20:45.500 --> 00:20:47.850
The same happened with
the recent reparations.

00:20:47.850 --> 00:20:50.330
My father received one
but at the same time,

00:20:50.330 --> 00:20:53.000
it was a huge discussion whether
you should receive reparations

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:57.780
for having been in prison
under-- or repent, you know,

00:20:57.780 --> 00:20:59.500
the national executive.

00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:02.920
So these sort of discussions are
building political narratives

00:21:02.920 --> 00:21:06.840
that do not have to do
with the crimes committed

00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:09.910
by the dictatorship and do not
have to do with the conditions

00:21:09.910 --> 00:21:11.570
in which we left to the exile.

00:21:11.570 --> 00:21:13.180
But actually daily
political life

00:21:13.180 --> 00:21:15.520
of constructing networks
once you are

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:17.210
in this position to accept.

00:21:17.210 --> 00:21:20.430
And that's I think what
makes this book different.

00:21:20.430 --> 00:21:22.730
Most of the other books,
they're not that many,

00:21:22.730 --> 00:21:26.050
but most of the other books
that I've seen, what they tried

00:21:26.050 --> 00:21:29.270
to do is to reconstruct the
source of the destruction

00:21:29.270 --> 00:21:30.770
of this community knowing

00:21:30.770 --> 00:21:34.860
and then consider how then
they say exile accentuates your

00:21:34.860 --> 00:21:37.810
natural craziness, which
is absolutely true.

00:21:37.810 --> 00:21:42.160
We were all absolutely insane
in many different ways just

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:45.670
so that you have
a taste of that.

00:21:45.670 --> 00:21:47.800
For a few months, I
would go into stores,

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:50.640
big stores like we had
Liverpool and stole things.

00:21:50.640 --> 00:21:53.970
And before getting to the door,
I would actually leave them

00:21:53.970 --> 00:21:56.470
by the door so that when I
was obtained by the police,

00:21:56.470 --> 00:21:59.000
I would actually start
shouting at them.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.650
We were very insane,
maybe different ways.

00:22:01.650 --> 00:22:03.970
But the interesting thing
is that this actually builds

00:22:03.970 --> 00:22:08.790
into networks that produce
interesting political results.

00:22:08.790 --> 00:22:11.880
And we're-- there's
reparation, a certain reparation

00:22:11.880 --> 00:22:13.850
that is done by the
community and by the networks

00:22:13.850 --> 00:22:15.580
that are formed in
the community.

00:22:15.580 --> 00:22:19.520
I think that's a wonderful
result of the book.

00:22:19.520 --> 00:22:21.320
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:33.750
[ Applause ]

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:35.190
&gt;&gt; Juan Uriagereka:
I have to apologize

00:22:35.190 --> 00:22:36.510
because I'm not a professional,

00:22:36.510 --> 00:22:42.280
so I wrote some notes
just to think about this.

00:22:42.280 --> 00:22:44.850
I was born in the '50s

00:22:44.850 --> 00:22:49.270
in a normal Spanish
family from Spain.

00:22:49.270 --> 00:22:53.110
President Eisenhower had
just ended the blockade

00:22:53.110 --> 00:22:57.470
that had us start
after the Great War.

00:22:57.470 --> 00:23:03.400
The alternative to invading with
Hitler in Mussolini defeated.

00:23:03.400 --> 00:23:06.020
It wouldn't have been easy
for the French or British

00:23:06.020 --> 00:23:09.830
who hadn't been willing to
stop fascism in its inception.

00:23:09.830 --> 00:23:13.330
Stalin was eager too but fearing
the west wanted the Soviets

00:23:13.330 --> 00:23:15.990
controlling the Mediterranean.

00:23:15.990 --> 00:23:19.630
Well over half a million people
had died in the Civil War,

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:23.030
Spanish Civil War,
including 200,000 executed

00:23:23.030 --> 00:23:27.610
in the [inaudible] and
other 50,000 were killed

00:23:27.610 --> 00:23:29.040
after the war ended.

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:31.930
Several thousand more died
in concentration camps.

00:23:31.930 --> 00:23:33.450
This is all in Spain.

00:23:33.450 --> 00:23:36.910
Some 200,000 became
permanent exiles.

00:23:36.910 --> 00:23:41.660
By the 1970s, about 4 million
had immigrated once it became

00:23:41.660 --> 00:23:46.660
legal in the 1940s in a
country of 27 million,

00:23:46.660 --> 00:23:48.840
again get the percentages.

00:23:48.840 --> 00:23:51.390
As I said, my family was normal.

00:23:51.390 --> 00:23:57.130
Some had survived the bombing of
Guernica that Picasso depicted.

00:23:57.130 --> 00:24:00.030
Others recounted that
in similar stories.

00:24:00.030 --> 00:24:03.080
I grew up in my grandparents'
[inaudible] farm

00:24:03.080 --> 00:24:07.100
as my father worked
for a company in exile.

00:24:07.100 --> 00:24:08.790
Mom learned to read
from another--

00:24:08.790 --> 00:24:12.810
from an urban teacher who
was relocated to our hamlet

00:24:12.810 --> 00:24:16.340
as a punishment for
having defended democracy.

00:24:16.340 --> 00:24:19.670
That was actually a break for
us peasants as he gave her

00:24:19.670 --> 00:24:21.930
and my uncles knowledge.

00:24:21.930 --> 00:24:23.420
Uncle Luis [assumed
spelling] was 15

00:24:23.420 --> 00:24:25.800
when he left for Argentina.

00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:30.380
Uncle Antonio, 14, half the
family was already in America.

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:35.100
In my mind, it was difficult to
figure out whether the letters

00:24:35.100 --> 00:24:37.910
that relatives sent
home were from exile,

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:40.560
immigration, prison or what.

00:24:40.560 --> 00:24:43.370
It was just a distant place.

00:24:43.370 --> 00:24:46.900
In the '60s, much
unrest happened

00:24:46.900 --> 00:24:50.150
in those remote places
of our relatives.

00:24:50.150 --> 00:24:54.150
Dad's company was then working
in Chile from where he wrote

00:24:54.150 --> 00:24:57.990
of hope, illegally
mailing books and records

00:24:57.990 --> 00:25:01.680
about Che Guevara
and by Violeta Parra.

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:05.740
Practically all the Spanish
writers I read then were exiles.

00:25:05.740 --> 00:25:09.440
During our transition to
democracy, many returned

00:25:09.440 --> 00:25:13.650
from the Southern Cone
escaping the dictatorships

00:25:13.650 --> 00:25:15.970
that we're talking about today.

00:25:15.970 --> 00:25:20.060
The book that we are
presenting brought a smile

00:25:20.060 --> 00:25:23.580
to my face reminding me of
my literary heroes, Onetti,

00:25:23.580 --> 00:25:26.150
Galeano, Benedetti, Perry Rossi
[assumed spelling], Soriano,

00:25:26.150 --> 00:25:29.850
Roa Bastos, or actors whose
skill impressed me the most,

00:25:29.850 --> 00:25:31.150
Alteri [assumed spelling],
Rossi [assumed spelling],

00:25:31.150 --> 00:25:32.450
Politi [assumed spelling].

00:25:32.450 --> 00:25:34.780
Not to speak of the
musicians whose songs we sang

00:25:34.780 --> 00:25:37.840
in the streets, [inaudible],
Sosa, Guevara,

00:25:37.840 --> 00:25:39.230
Warani [assumed spelling].

00:25:39.230 --> 00:25:42.760
Our book notes on page
73, the difficulty

00:25:42.760 --> 00:25:46.900
that American exiles had in
Europe echoing the complaint

00:25:46.900 --> 00:25:50.230
by Perry Rossi that I
remember very vividly.

00:25:50.230 --> 00:25:53.050
That being said,
my dearest friends,

00:25:53.050 --> 00:25:55.000
were those marginalized
intellectuals.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.540
Some of whom taught
me everything I know

00:25:57.540 --> 00:26:01.390
about the theater, like the late
Claudio Narea [assumed spelling]

00:26:01.390 --> 00:26:04.160
after learning his
craft from [inaudible].

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:06.280
I can't imagine the
Spanish movie there,

00:26:06.280 --> 00:26:08.700
the "Almodóvar" made famous

00:26:08.700 --> 00:26:12.150
without the likes
of Cecilia Roth.

00:26:12.150 --> 00:26:15.770
And so I can't help asking
what really happened,

00:26:15.770 --> 00:26:19.510
why this ties back and forth.

00:26:19.510 --> 00:26:22.690
I sent this on page 187.

00:26:22.690 --> 00:26:27.180
This is so that you
see I read the book--

00:26:27.180 --> 00:26:30.880
reads, "whether clothed in
military or civilian guard,

00:26:30.880 --> 00:26:34.840
authoritarianism has
been a mainstay."

00:26:34.840 --> 00:26:36.750
While the book is talking
about Latin America,

00:26:36.750 --> 00:26:38.570
the motherland is no different.

00:26:38.570 --> 00:26:41.870
In the two plus century
since the French Revolution,

00:26:41.870 --> 00:26:47.140
one can count 25, 25
military [inaudible].

00:26:47.140 --> 00:26:49.550
I don't care whether from
the right or from the left,

00:26:49.550 --> 00:26:52.110
military [inaudible]
in 200 years.

00:26:52.110 --> 00:26:54.210
The latest one in 1981,

00:26:54.210 --> 00:26:57.760
five years before Spain
joined the European Union,

00:26:57.760 --> 00:27:00.780
still unclear who was behind it.

00:27:00.780 --> 00:27:04.810
During the 19th century, liberal
and conservative administrations

00:27:04.810 --> 00:27:08.010
so commonly replace one
another after a coup.

00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:10.730
That by the time the
monarchy was reestablished,

00:27:10.730 --> 00:27:13.290
they institutionalize
succession of government.

00:27:13.290 --> 00:27:17.250
So the opposite side routinely
change in every two years.

00:27:17.250 --> 00:27:19.720
Alas, that Solomonic
solution didn't last long

00:27:19.720 --> 00:27:22.680
because both were
incredibly corrupt.

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:24.600
Eventually further coups led

00:27:24.600 --> 00:27:27.490
to the famous dictatorships
of the 20th century.

00:27:27.490 --> 00:27:31.050
As the book describes,
the fate of these dynamics

00:27:31.050 --> 00:27:37.170
on page 32 citing Luna
involved [foreign language],

00:27:37.170 --> 00:27:43.590
that is prison, expulsion or
entombment, so the dark aspects.

00:27:43.590 --> 00:27:47.500
And not all is bad that
stems from such chaos.

00:27:47.500 --> 00:27:51.150
It may have been harder to
otherwise realize the liberation

00:27:51.150 --> 00:27:55.500
of American and Asian colonies
throughout the 19th century

00:27:55.500 --> 00:27:58.490
or the African ones
during the 20th century.

00:27:58.490 --> 00:28:02.430
Just as not always good either
in the visionary governments

00:28:02.430 --> 00:28:06.080
that stemmed from uprisings
like the French revolution.

00:28:06.080 --> 00:28:10.440
The Napoleonic standardization
fueled resentment leading

00:28:10.440 --> 00:28:13.440
to successful fascist
nationalisms from Italy

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:18.470
to Germany to unsuccessful ones
from Iberia to the Vulcans.

00:28:18.470 --> 00:28:21.550
Later still lingering conflicts.

00:28:21.550 --> 00:28:23.340
Look at the Catalan one.

00:28:23.340 --> 00:28:27.570
Often find a trigger in
Civil Wars of that ilk.

00:28:27.570 --> 00:28:32.980
As David Armitage reminds
us, I am a revolutionary,

00:28:32.980 --> 00:28:38.190
you are a rebel, and they
are engaged in the Civil War.

00:28:38.190 --> 00:28:39.490
This is why the question

00:28:39.490 --> 00:28:41.780
of whether nationalistic
movements are good

00:28:41.780 --> 00:28:43.730
or bad has no easy answer.

00:28:43.730 --> 00:28:46.880
After all, we describe by
the same word, the Mapuche

00:28:46.880 --> 00:28:49.420
or the [inaudible]
nation, and the Russian

00:28:49.420 --> 00:28:51.390
and the Chinese nation.

00:28:51.390 --> 00:28:55.610
Such dynamics are structure
for me in a deep sense,

00:28:55.610 --> 00:28:58.220
and this is the linguist
in me talking now.

00:28:58.220 --> 00:29:01.320
Within material science,
physical tensions

00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:05.230
of this sort are called
dynamical frustration.

00:29:05.230 --> 00:29:08.760
We may think of it as the
unresolvable coexistence

00:29:08.760 --> 00:29:12.690
of conflicting tendencies
that never settle.

00:29:12.690 --> 00:29:15.260
For those raised in
the Marxist tradition,

00:29:15.260 --> 00:29:18.290
dynamical frustration
relates to the Hegelian clash

00:29:18.290 --> 00:29:21.900
between thesis and antithesis
except you never achieve

00:29:21.900 --> 00:29:23.200
a synthesis.

00:29:23.200 --> 00:29:25.990
Or if you wish, the synthesis
is a state of equilibrium

00:29:25.990 --> 00:29:29.230
that arises from
the clash itself.

00:29:29.230 --> 00:29:32.020
I raised the idea because
yet a further ingredient

00:29:32.020 --> 00:29:33.880
in the cauldron, one leading

00:29:33.880 --> 00:29:37.770
to the exiles we are now
considering is radicalism

00:29:37.770 --> 00:29:39.890
and reaction to liberalism.

00:29:39.890 --> 00:29:43.270
It is fascinating how liberal
and radical forces ally

00:29:43.270 --> 00:29:46.840
to defeat conservatives
in the form of fascism.

00:29:46.840 --> 00:29:50.620
Although, first liberalism
aligned with conservatism

00:29:50.620 --> 00:29:54.550
to keep radicalism confined
to the east, Russia and so on.

00:29:54.550 --> 00:29:57.580
And less than a decade later,
the logical combination closed

00:29:57.580 --> 00:30:00.610
with at least in
Europe conservatism

00:30:00.610 --> 00:30:04.860
and radicalism uniting over
how to partition Poland.

00:30:04.860 --> 00:30:08.720
In this light, one can read
the second A bomb in Nagasaki

00:30:08.720 --> 00:30:13.330
under liberal reluctance to let
Stalin go for Franco and Salazar

00:30:13.330 --> 00:30:15.100
as the new dynamical frustration

00:30:15.100 --> 00:30:18.570
which crystallizes
into the Cold War.

00:30:18.570 --> 00:30:20.280
The book has several
further examples

00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:24.320
of dynamical frustration
beyond that Cold War.

00:30:24.320 --> 00:30:27.240
We are reminded of the
vicious circle in which fear

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:30.530
of revolution brings
about repression

00:30:30.530 --> 00:30:35.060
which fuels the desire
for revolution and so on.

00:30:35.060 --> 00:30:37.610
Or different instantiations
of modernity

00:30:37.610 --> 00:30:40.530
when the ideological
path concocted

00:30:40.530 --> 00:30:45.260
in the west an urban reality
confirms the multifarious nature

00:30:45.260 --> 00:30:50.270
of the rural colonial or
frontier realities beyond.

00:30:50.270 --> 00:30:53.390
Indeed, these revolutions,
rebellions, civil wars,

00:30:53.390 --> 00:30:59.180
whatever you want to call
them that led to the creation

00:30:59.180 --> 00:31:01.250
of the very nations
we're talking about,

00:31:01.250 --> 00:31:03.980
from the Spanish empire
and from one another.

00:31:03.980 --> 00:31:08.470
Those are all prime examples
of dynamical frustration.

00:31:08.470 --> 00:31:10.970
All these dynamics
are frustrating

00:31:10.970 --> 00:31:13.750
and including the fact

00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:17.200
that exile is both
welcomed and threatened.

00:31:17.200 --> 00:31:19.360
And this is another
quote from the book,

00:31:19.360 --> 00:31:23.160
"You who left are now
returning like heroes and we

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:26.620
who stayed behind are
the ones who suffered."

00:31:26.620 --> 00:31:31.220
Those are the inxiles [phonetic]
that are mentioned in the book.

00:31:31.220 --> 00:31:33.550
Those are very complicated
dynamics with--

00:31:33.550 --> 00:31:37.150
There is no right or wrong here.

00:31:37.150 --> 00:31:39.670
The book also interestingly
brings

00:31:39.670 --> 00:31:43.010
to the equation the
unintended consequence of exile

00:31:43.010 --> 00:31:44.710
in a globalized world.

00:31:44.710 --> 00:31:48.510
The media related, university
and culturally driven,

00:31:48.510 --> 00:31:51.560
and ultimately politically
effective role of exiles

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:53.490
in making their countries
change.

00:31:53.490 --> 00:31:57.260
Another example of this
earlier on is what intellectuals

00:31:57.260 --> 00:31:58.560
from Nazi Germany did.

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:02.130
That's one of the main pillars
of the American University.

00:32:02.130 --> 00:32:05.340
The book puts it on-- book
on page 26 as followed,

00:32:05.340 --> 00:32:08.950
in the long run, exile
backfired given the connections

00:32:08.950 --> 00:32:13.270
established by exiles and the
resonance their plight received,

00:32:13.270 --> 00:32:15.300
perhaps partly as a result,

00:32:15.300 --> 00:32:19.330
while the Spanish dictatorship
lasted four decades, 39 years.

00:32:19.330 --> 00:32:22.240
And ones whose effects were
examined with the exception

00:32:22.240 --> 00:32:25.780
of Paraguay, which is almost
as long as the Spanish were

00:32:25.780 --> 00:32:28.830
between half and a fifth
shorter, depending.

00:32:28.830 --> 00:32:32.760
Now, that allowed for larger
role of the exiled communities.

00:32:32.760 --> 00:32:35.530
That's what chapter
7 mainly is about.

00:32:35.530 --> 00:32:39.070
And what chapter 5 goes into,
procedures for repatriation

00:32:39.070 --> 00:32:41.090
that we were discussing,
investigation,

00:32:41.090 --> 00:32:42.880
eventually fair trials, again,

00:32:42.880 --> 00:32:45.350
with the interesting
exception of Paraguay.

00:32:45.350 --> 00:32:49.200
Situation in Spain
aligns more with Paraguay

00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:52.460
than the more democratic
Argentinean nations.

00:32:52.460 --> 00:32:56.880
Argentina, Chile and
especially Uruguay

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:02.130
where you have a former diplomat
are becoming the head of state.

00:33:02.130 --> 00:33:04.830
For a member of a
comparable armed group--

00:33:04.830 --> 00:33:07.770
armed group in Spain, that
would be just unthinkable.

00:33:07.770 --> 00:33:10.200
Indeed, the moral
debate about arm struggle

00:33:10.200 --> 00:33:13.810
that chapter 6 raises, extremely
interesting, inconceivable

00:33:13.810 --> 00:33:17.180
in a country that only a
couple of weeks ago was ruled

00:33:17.180 --> 00:33:19.750
against by the European
Court of Human Rights

00:33:19.750 --> 00:33:22.610
for jailing activists
after burning effigies

00:33:22.610 --> 00:33:28.590
of the king whose role in the
coup d'etat is still murky.

00:33:28.590 --> 00:33:33.980
Despite the fact that as
the book notes on page 70,

00:33:33.980 --> 00:33:38.110
Southern Cone exiles had a hard
time explaining their messy

00:33:38.110 --> 00:33:39.810
politics to Europeans.

00:33:39.810 --> 00:33:41.110
This is still the case.

00:33:41.110 --> 00:33:42.650
It's very difficult
to understand

00:33:42.650 --> 00:33:44.690
by European standards.

00:33:44.690 --> 00:33:47.330
Spanish exiles with a more
traditional message were not

00:33:47.330 --> 00:33:51.130
able to summon action
against Franco who died in bed

00:33:51.130 --> 00:33:54.680
and as he wished, leaving
things very well bounded.

00:33:54.680 --> 00:33:58.230
To this date, speaking in
Spain not just of reparation

00:33:58.230 --> 00:34:02.250
or restoration, but even
investigation is taboo.

00:34:02.250 --> 00:34:06.140
It is presently inconceivable
to find a situation equivalent

00:34:06.140 --> 00:34:09.800
to what the book discusses
on page 149 where the day

00:34:09.800 --> 00:34:12.880
of the national stop rising in
Spain turns into a national day

00:34:12.880 --> 00:34:14.870
of memory, truth and justice

00:34:14.870 --> 00:34:18.540
as is the case in
the Southern Cone.

00:34:18.540 --> 00:34:22.710
Chapter 8 speaks of shifting
frontiers of citizenships,

00:34:22.710 --> 00:34:24.660
exploring transnational
networks,

00:34:24.660 --> 00:34:26.660
topic that fascinates me.

00:34:26.660 --> 00:34:29.680
This can be seen as
a new phenomenon.

00:34:29.680 --> 00:34:34.150
Describing present migratory
processes, this is a quote

00:34:34.150 --> 00:34:37.960
as having complicated, the
possibility of defining diaspora

00:34:37.960 --> 00:34:41.450
in purely ethnonational terms.

00:34:41.450 --> 00:34:43.290
But this is now me.

00:34:43.290 --> 00:34:45.570
I would say modern notions

00:34:45.570 --> 00:34:50.820
like nation itself are liberal
inventions of the 19th century,

00:34:50.820 --> 00:34:53.200
while Diasporas are many, many,

00:34:53.200 --> 00:34:56.170
many tens of thousands
of years older.

00:34:56.170 --> 00:34:58.810
Before the birth
of nation states,

00:34:58.810 --> 00:35:00.960
those were immigration dynamics,

00:35:00.960 --> 00:35:03.930
not conquest ones
for the most part.

00:35:03.930 --> 00:35:08.610
Now, mere emigrants built
humanity as we understand it.

00:35:08.610 --> 00:35:12.060
Interbreeding for example with
Neanderthals and Denisovans

00:35:12.060 --> 00:35:15.120
to yield the miracles
of art and myth.

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:19.570
Those errant Jews and gypsies
and aborigines and Indians

00:35:19.570 --> 00:35:22.460
and other expatriates
of all kinds,

00:35:22.460 --> 00:35:25.830
those are the holders
of human existence.

00:35:25.830 --> 00:35:29.910
Only very slow time in evolution
will tell whether it's dynamical

00:35:29.910 --> 00:35:32.720
frustrations lead to
emergent structures

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:35.480
that we may call
forward thinking.

00:35:35.480 --> 00:35:38.910
Certainly new realities
will emerge that way too.

00:35:38.910 --> 00:35:43.130
Witness the web,
witness social media.

00:35:43.130 --> 00:35:46.790
The way art did-- and
eventually writing,

00:35:46.790 --> 00:35:50.440
and eventually the printing
press, all as momentous

00:35:50.440 --> 00:35:51.890
as the internet these days.

00:35:51.890 --> 00:35:59.320
In our world, it may not be
all that bad to start dreaming

00:35:59.320 --> 00:36:02.160
of electronic exiles,
because one runs

00:36:02.160 --> 00:36:04.880
out of physical locations to
take the children to in case

00:36:04.880 --> 00:36:08.690
of real and tangible
civil wars or familiar

00:36:08.690 --> 00:36:11.330
and not electronic prisons.

00:36:11.330 --> 00:36:16.110
Thinking of normal families in
Syria, Iraq does make me wonder.

00:36:16.110 --> 00:36:19.950
Our book cites Perry Rossi's
line representing the dilemma

00:36:19.950 --> 00:36:24.880
of exile, "to part
is to part in half."

00:36:24.880 --> 00:36:30.270
It echoes the one
line that Cole Parker,

00:36:30.270 --> 00:36:33.600
adapting that unforgettable
goodbye,

00:36:33.600 --> 00:36:35.730
which is to die a little.

00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:38.750
Then again, the horrors
we continue to witness

00:36:38.750 --> 00:36:42.950
in other authoritarian
societies remind us

00:36:42.950 --> 00:36:46.200
that to die is to part a lot.

00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:49.920
So let's hope that
before the finale exile,

00:36:49.920 --> 00:36:52.370
we leave our children in a
more democratic, transparent,

00:36:52.370 --> 00:36:56.040
pluralistic world of the sort
our dear exiles fought for,

00:36:56.040 --> 00:37:00.190
successfully in that
they kept our hope alive.

00:37:00.190 --> 00:37:03.570
This is one tangible legacy
of this wonderful book.

00:37:03.570 --> 00:37:07.570
Well beyond the accurate facts
and testimonies in regard

00:37:07.570 --> 00:37:09.600
to institutional transformation.

00:37:09.600 --> 00:37:13.430
As it notes on page
187, electoral democracy

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:16.250
and the periodic change
of government seem

00:37:16.250 --> 00:37:18.460
to have taken a firm hold.

00:37:18.460 --> 00:37:21.190
It is uplifting to see such
a comprehensive analysis

00:37:21.190 --> 00:37:26.700
of exile placed in the context
and exploring without anger,

00:37:26.700 --> 00:37:30.750
even nostalgia, how it
contribute to the development

00:37:30.750 --> 00:37:34.740
of democracy in countries
where that exile originated

00:37:34.740 --> 00:37:37.080
and in countries like
my own where it ended.

00:37:37.080 --> 00:37:38.880
Thank you.

00:37:38.880 --> 00:37:46.170
[ Applause ]

00:37:46.170 --> 00:37:49.670
