00:37:49.670 --> 00:37:54.730
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: If
Roniger should join us.

00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:58.000
I could hear his comments.

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.600
So let me tell you
something about,

00:38:00.600 --> 00:38:05.290
one of the difficulties
in writing this book.

00:38:05.290 --> 00:38:09.910
There are four of us,
as I mentioned before

00:38:09.910 --> 00:38:15.700
from different disciplines,
with writing habits

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:20.990
that are very far
one from the other.

00:38:20.990 --> 00:38:24.410
And Luis Roniger and Mario
Sznajder collaborated

00:38:24.410 --> 00:38:29.240
on a number of books, so they
knew each other fairly well.

00:38:29.240 --> 00:38:35.310
Leonardo Senkman and I wrote
one book together about fascism

00:38:35.310 --> 00:38:39.540
and Nazism in Argentine letters.

00:38:39.540 --> 00:38:47.050
But Leo Senkman has one way of
writing and one way of thinking

00:38:47.050 --> 00:38:50.280
that is about, I don't
know, whether 180 degrees,

00:38:50.280 --> 00:38:54.620
but at least 90 degrees
away from my own.

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:59.780
And that was one of
the difficulties,

00:38:59.780 --> 00:39:03.100
trying to find a common
voice, how are we going

00:39:03.100 --> 00:39:07.060
to find some sort of language

00:39:07.060 --> 00:39:10.280
that will accommodate
the perspectives

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:12.930
from which we were coming.

00:39:12.930 --> 00:39:16.950
The other thing is each one of
us has a very different style

00:39:16.950 --> 00:39:20.330
of work and there
is one among us

00:39:20.330 --> 00:39:23.480
who is the most workaholic
of all.

00:39:23.480 --> 00:39:25.130
No, it's not me.

00:39:25.130 --> 00:39:28.730
It is Luis Roniger.

00:39:28.730 --> 00:39:32.450
And he is the one who
really kept us in line.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:37.400
And so, in addition to all the
merits of his scholarly work

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:40.420
and so on, I have to tell
you that he is really--

00:39:40.420 --> 00:39:43.820
I don't want to say slave
driver, it's not nice,

00:39:43.820 --> 00:39:52.040
but he's the one who kept
us on track and partly it's

00:39:52.040 --> 00:39:54.990
because he also has a secret
weapon, his wife Shirley

00:39:54.990 --> 00:39:59.670
who is the one who also
did the index for the book,

00:39:59.670 --> 00:40:05.730
a rather awesome task for which
all authors are most grateful

00:40:05.730 --> 00:40:07.030
to you, Shirley.

00:40:07.030 --> 00:40:08.570
Thank you.

00:40:08.570 --> 00:40:14.850
Let me turn this over to
Luis and who is partly

00:40:14.850 --> 00:40:17.090
to a good degree
responsible for the fact

00:40:17.090 --> 00:40:19.580
that we were able
to finish this book.

00:40:19.580 --> 00:40:20.880
Luis.

00:40:20.880 --> 00:40:22.680
&gt;&gt; Luis Roniger: Thank you.

00:40:22.680 --> 00:40:26.990
[ Applause ]

00:40:26.990 --> 00:40:29.640
&gt;&gt; Luis Roniger: Thank you,
Saúl, for your kind words.

00:40:29.640 --> 00:40:35.760
And thank you Ernesto and Juan
for the generous evaluation,

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:38.690
talk about the book
and also sharing your

00:40:38.690 --> 00:40:39.990
personal perspective.

00:40:39.990 --> 00:40:45.990
And listening to you, I would
like to say that what is exile

00:40:45.990 --> 00:40:50.180
and what is the key that
brings such creativities,

00:40:50.180 --> 00:40:55.230
such innovation, not just to
the countries that we analyze

00:40:55.230 --> 00:40:59.680
but overall there is an open
possibility that [inaudible].

00:40:59.680 --> 00:41:08.450
And the idea of exile is that
at least in the modern world,

00:41:08.450 --> 00:41:13.030
it breaks the hyphen
between nation and state.

00:41:13.030 --> 00:41:17.220
Whenever people are forced
to flee their own countries,

00:41:17.220 --> 00:41:20.150
they are no longer obligated.

00:41:20.150 --> 00:41:26.160
They cannot take the markers
of that certainty for granted.

00:41:26.160 --> 00:41:28.560
They cannot take their
common assumptions

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:31.800
for granted, something
has broken.

00:41:31.800 --> 00:41:34.590
In the nation state,
collective identity

00:41:34.590 --> 00:41:37.300
and political rights
are built together.

00:41:37.300 --> 00:41:40.780
This is the hyphen
between nation and state.

00:41:40.780 --> 00:41:46.120
But once they leave, they
cling even more to the nation

00:41:46.120 --> 00:41:48.650
but they are no longer
committed to the state.

00:41:48.650 --> 00:41:52.990
And these open a range of
possibilities of learning,

00:41:52.990 --> 00:41:57.760
of getting to use new-- getting
used to new institutions,

00:41:57.760 --> 00:42:02.440
new forms of interacting,
new forms of partnership,

00:42:02.440 --> 00:42:07.980
even the very conception of
being in a relationship changed.

00:42:07.980 --> 00:42:15.260
And as you know, many in exile
have eventually broken apart

00:42:15.260 --> 00:42:21.890
diverse as being a
characteristic of--

00:42:21.890 --> 00:42:25.350
thank you, diverse as being
a characteristic of exile.

00:42:25.350 --> 00:42:30.420
And there are many losses of
exile, but there are also gains.

00:42:30.420 --> 00:42:34.260
This possibility of opening
themselves to new ideas,

00:42:34.260 --> 00:42:36.940
to new forms of understanding
the world,

00:42:36.940 --> 00:42:40.530
understanding politics pays off.

00:42:40.530 --> 00:42:42.640
Because together
with the losses,

00:42:42.640 --> 00:42:47.850
and losses certainly are
numerous and countless

00:42:47.850 --> 00:42:55.250
and have been a-- both
in personal terms,

00:42:55.250 --> 00:42:57.310
in terms of the life
of people going

00:42:57.310 --> 00:42:59.740
to exile, many, many losses.

00:42:59.740 --> 00:43:04.230
But also gains not just
individually, not just in terms

00:43:04.230 --> 00:43:09.230
of human capital but things
that will eventually come

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:11.480
to serve the countries
of origin.

00:43:11.480 --> 00:43:15.040
People will remain
attached to their countries,

00:43:15.040 --> 00:43:20.460
to their background and
once the possibility opens,

00:43:20.460 --> 00:43:24.530
they should consider
whether to return.

00:43:24.530 --> 00:43:27.690
And though-- although
the return, the word,

00:43:27.690 --> 00:43:31.310
is in the title of the book, we
emphasized throughout the book

00:43:31.310 --> 00:43:34.860
that this is just one
possibility among many.

00:43:34.860 --> 00:43:38.270
And therefore there are
not just the returnees

00:43:38.270 --> 00:43:39.990
that we should consider.

00:43:39.990 --> 00:43:42.980
There are the sojourners
that people who stay abroad

00:43:42.980 --> 00:43:48.210
but maintain relationship
with others in the diaspora.

00:43:48.210 --> 00:43:52.900
And let me-- beyond
the individual gains,

00:43:52.900 --> 00:43:57.790
it mentioned something about the
contributions to the country.

00:43:57.790 --> 00:43:59.700
Let's start with politics.

00:43:59.700 --> 00:44:06.430
We cannot understand the
transition from authoritarianism

00:44:06.430 --> 00:44:09.660
to democracy in some
of those countries

00:44:09.660 --> 00:44:11.790
without considering exile.

00:44:11.790 --> 00:44:14.050
The most evident
case among the four

00:44:14.050 --> 00:44:17.800
that we consider is
the case of Chile.

00:44:17.800 --> 00:44:22.880
In Chile, exiles were
crucial in the transition

00:44:22.880 --> 00:44:26.280
but because they were
crucial while in exile,

00:44:26.280 --> 00:44:30.220
they recompose the
political alliances,

00:44:30.220 --> 00:44:32.730
the socialist change
their attitude,

00:44:32.730 --> 00:44:35.020
broke ranks with the communist.

00:44:35.020 --> 00:44:38.040
Within the communist
there were also divisions.

00:44:38.040 --> 00:44:42.120
Eventually they build a
coalition of 17 countries.

00:44:42.120 --> 00:44:46.030
This is called the [inaudible]
that led to the defeat

00:44:46.030 --> 00:44:48.780
of Pinochet in the
referendum of 1998

00:44:48.780 --> 00:44:53.540
and eventually opened
the door to transition.

00:44:53.540 --> 00:44:59.110
But also in the cabinet of the
successive governments that came

00:44:59.110 --> 00:45:04.460
after the transition, exiles
played a crucial role.

00:45:04.460 --> 00:45:09.000
Even-- in terms of their numbers
among the cabinet members you

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:10.960
can trace exiles.

00:45:10.960 --> 00:45:14.860
They were a prevailing force.

00:45:14.860 --> 00:45:20.160
In Uruguay for example, Danilo
Astori, the vice president

00:45:20.160 --> 00:45:23.680
of President Mujica
was an exile.

00:45:23.680 --> 00:45:27.000
The minister of education,
Ricardo Ehrlich was an exile.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:29.590
They were also scientists,
but they moved

00:45:29.590 --> 00:45:32.340
into politics beyond
the politics

00:45:32.340 --> 00:45:35.280
of the university
then in academia.

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:37.360
In academia in Uruguay
for example,

00:45:37.360 --> 00:45:42.650
until 1984 there was just
one university, the UdelaR,

00:45:42.650 --> 00:45:47.200
Universidad de la Republica,
exiles opened a range

00:45:47.200 --> 00:45:53.610
to new universities, new
disciplines, new investment

00:45:53.610 --> 00:45:56.340
in science and technology.

00:45:56.340 --> 00:46:01.190
For example in biology, in
the biological sciences,

00:46:01.190 --> 00:46:06.780
there were five tenure position
before the exiles returned.

00:46:06.780 --> 00:46:13.420
As exiles started returning,
they build a faculty of 100,

00:46:13.420 --> 00:46:16.200
over 100, they invested
millions.

00:46:16.200 --> 00:46:19.030
They used their connections
with France,

00:46:19.030 --> 00:46:22.310
with Mexico to create
new avenues,

00:46:22.310 --> 00:46:27.320
new subdisciplines,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:46:27.320 --> 00:46:32.500
Three of the four provosts in
Uruguay following the return

00:46:32.500 --> 00:46:38.430
of democracy were exiles,
and some of them were very,

00:46:38.430 --> 00:46:44.220
very instrumental in revamping
the entire educational system

00:46:44.220 --> 00:46:50.420
of higher ed-- entire system
of higher education in Uruguay

00:46:50.420 --> 00:46:54.620
in the realm of new disciplines.

00:46:54.620 --> 00:46:57.990
For example in Chile there
was no social history

00:46:57.990 --> 00:47:03.920
until Gabriel Salazar
returned to Chile.

00:47:03.920 --> 00:47:09.000
Bioethics, in Argentina
there was no sense

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:14.560
of what is the ethics in
dealing with biological research

00:47:14.560 --> 00:47:18.660
until somebody who did
his career in the US,

00:47:18.660 --> 00:47:21.610
Victor Penchaszadeh,
returned to Argentina

00:47:21.610 --> 00:47:26.030
and opened a new ground
supporting also the mothers

00:47:26.030 --> 00:47:29.590
and especially the
grandmothers of Plaza de Mayo

00:47:29.590 --> 00:47:32.430
and eventually created
a new field

00:47:32.430 --> 00:47:37.030
of research and investigation.

00:47:37.030 --> 00:47:40.450
In the publishing industry,
in each of the four countries,

00:47:40.450 --> 00:47:49.340
you can find people who
recreated the impetus

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:52.730
that existed in the
'60s once back

00:47:52.730 --> 00:47:54.960
in their countries after exile.

00:47:54.960 --> 00:47:57.470
Let me mentions some of them.

00:47:57.470 --> 00:48:01.690
Divinsky in Ediciones de
la Flor en in Argentina.

00:48:01.690 --> 00:48:06.250
Pablo Harari, he founded
Editorial Trilce in Uruguay.

00:48:06.250 --> 00:48:09.360
Carlos Orellana in Chile.

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:15.490
In the case of Paraguay,
[inaudible] by himself

00:48:15.490 --> 00:48:19.490
on its own effort, as you
know Paraguay is a totally

00:48:19.490 --> 00:48:20.790
different universe.

00:48:20.790 --> 00:48:23.280
It's a universe of
an oral culture,

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:26.050
not necessarily a
written culture.

00:48:26.050 --> 00:48:30.560
But he managed somehow to
eventually fail in the long run

00:48:30.560 --> 00:48:32.730
because Paraguay is Paraguay

00:48:32.730 --> 00:48:37.370
with not enough readership,
but he tried so hard.

00:48:37.370 --> 00:48:42.630
And other people who did not
go into exile collaborated

00:48:42.630 --> 00:48:47.840
with people in exile,
exiles coming back.

00:48:47.840 --> 00:48:54.860
And for instance the
first-- a film, a long--

00:48:54.860 --> 00:49:00.340
a feature film in Paraguay
was done by a returnee.

00:49:00.340 --> 00:49:10.370
"Miramenometokei" was the
name of this film in 2002.

00:49:10.370 --> 00:49:16.780
And also, there were failures of
course, institutional failures.

00:49:16.780 --> 00:49:21.100
One may ask why the democracy
in Uruguay or democracy

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:24.580
in Chile seems to have overcome

00:49:24.580 --> 00:49:28.450
to a larger extent
the polarization,

00:49:28.450 --> 00:49:33.170
political polarization down
the democracy in Argentina.

00:49:33.170 --> 00:49:37.940
A part of this story is
that the contributions

00:49:37.940 --> 00:49:41.260
of exiles is not enough.

00:49:41.260 --> 00:49:47.650
It is the meeting point between
the ability of the exiles,

00:49:47.650 --> 00:49:50.620
the willingness to do
something for the country

00:49:50.620 --> 00:49:54.160
and eventually the
long-term conditions

00:49:54.160 --> 00:49:59.740
that enable those
contributions to be pervasive

00:49:59.740 --> 00:50:03.160
or be fleeting away
and disappear.

00:50:03.160 --> 00:50:05.410
In the case of Argentina,

00:50:05.410 --> 00:50:09.310
we have with initial
democratization starting

00:50:09.310 --> 00:50:15.780
on December of 1983, we have
very important contributions

00:50:15.780 --> 00:50:20.080
in science for example
with Sadosky

00:50:20.080 --> 00:50:25.430
which democratized the
entire system of academia.

00:50:25.430 --> 00:50:30.900
They [inaudible] and
try to democratize it,

00:50:30.900 --> 00:50:36.730
and that the realm of
politics the group of Esmeralda

00:50:36.730 --> 00:50:40.610
who were the advisers
to president Alfonsin

00:50:40.610 --> 00:50:46.740
and wrote these discourses
as was mentioned before.

00:50:46.740 --> 00:50:53.090
The Cultura Sosyalista that was
supposed to be an open ground--

00:50:53.090 --> 00:50:57.320
an open meeting ground for
people to debate the ideas

00:50:57.320 --> 00:51:01.640
without political polarization.

00:51:01.640 --> 00:51:07.180
Nonetheless, politics are
at large and the connection

00:51:07.180 --> 00:51:09.930
between politics and
the political economy

00:51:09.930 --> 00:51:11.890
for Argentina failed.

00:51:11.890 --> 00:51:16.270
And as you know, there were many
waves and ups and downs both

00:51:16.270 --> 00:51:20.350
in transition of justice
and the recreation

00:51:20.350 --> 00:51:21.700
of democratic culture.

00:51:21.700 --> 00:51:25.270
But nonetheless, the
level of civil society,

00:51:25.270 --> 00:51:28.440
the transformation was
there to stay and as a--

00:51:28.440 --> 00:51:34.380
and despite the institution
imbalances that we see

00:51:34.380 --> 00:51:38.580
in Argentina and
still the tradition

00:51:38.580 --> 00:51:40.440
of political polarization,

00:51:40.440 --> 00:51:46.200
Argentina of the 2010
is not the same in terms

00:51:46.200 --> 00:51:49.400
of embracing human rights.

00:51:49.400 --> 00:51:55.290
It has gained a lot
in that support.

00:52:00.700 --> 00:52:07.580
I think that political exiling
Latin America has something

00:52:07.580 --> 00:52:13.390
to say-- something of
comparative relevance

00:52:13.390 --> 00:52:16.320
for other regions of the world.

00:52:16.320 --> 00:52:23.100
And we are-- before Juan started
mentioning the case and talking

00:52:23.100 --> 00:52:29.460
about the case of Spain
and this brings me--

00:52:29.460 --> 00:52:33.890
it brings to my mind
also the case of Germany.

00:52:33.890 --> 00:52:37.690
Case of Germany and in
the case of this space.

00:52:37.690 --> 00:52:40.990
There's not been a
re-accommodation of exiles

00:52:40.990 --> 00:52:44.890
as in the case of
the Southern Cone

00:52:44.890 --> 00:52:48.800
and in particular I would
say the case of Uruguay,

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:52.470
then followed by the case of
Chile, the case of Argentina,

00:52:52.470 --> 00:52:55.590
and finally the case
of Paraguay.

00:52:55.590 --> 00:52:58.050
Various degrees of
accommodation,

00:52:58.050 --> 00:53:02.810
but there's been a willingness
somehow after initial period

00:53:02.810 --> 00:53:08.360
of resistance to
re-accommodate exiles

00:53:08.360 --> 00:53:10.690
and give exiles the
proper place.

00:53:10.690 --> 00:53:14.700
Of course Uruguay is at the top
because in the case of Uruguay,

00:53:14.700 --> 00:53:19.470
they decided to bring the
people who lose their jobs

00:53:19.470 --> 00:53:21.310
in the public administration.

00:53:21.310 --> 00:53:23.270
They are called the exonerados.

00:53:23.270 --> 00:53:25.630
This was the word that was used.

00:53:25.630 --> 00:53:29.010
People who lost their
position, what they were thrown

00:53:29.010 --> 00:53:34.360
out of work and then many
of them left for exile.

00:53:34.360 --> 00:53:39.440
With democratization, Uruguay
decided to bring them back

00:53:39.440 --> 00:53:41.970
to their former positions.

00:53:41.970 --> 00:53:45.210
For instance, Samuel
Lichtensztejn who was

00:53:45.210 --> 00:53:49.530
in the '70s, in the early
'70s the provost of UdelaR,

00:53:49.530 --> 00:53:55.220
of the Universidad-- Universidad
de la Republica was brought back

00:53:55.220 --> 00:53:59.240
in the '80s and given
his old post.

00:53:59.240 --> 00:54:04.930
Now with a new perspective and
new exposure, a new context,

00:54:04.930 --> 00:54:07.970
transnational connections,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:54:07.970 --> 00:54:15.790
And this is a fantastic push for
institutional transformation.

00:54:15.790 --> 00:54:18.890
In the case of Germany, they--

00:54:18.890 --> 00:54:23.400
Even the word exiles
was not used

00:54:23.400 --> 00:54:28.830
for the people who fled Nazism.

00:54:28.830 --> 00:54:31.460
The word [inaudible],
those who were pushed

00:54:31.460 --> 00:54:35.500
out from their own land
was used for those who are

00:54:35.500 --> 00:54:41.070
to leave East Germany and
were received in West Germany.

00:54:41.070 --> 00:54:46.290
This-- even the label
recognizing

00:54:46.290 --> 00:54:49.250
that something wrong
are being committed

00:54:49.250 --> 00:54:53.080
against them was
not granted them.

00:54:53.080 --> 00:54:56.390
And the same with
the case of Spain

00:54:56.390 --> 00:55:01.710
that you saw wonderfully
exposed [inaudible].

00:55:01.710 --> 00:55:12.890
And certainly in Spain the-- if
they have received the figures

00:55:12.890 --> 00:55:18.580
of intellectuals, they
have tried somehow

00:55:18.580 --> 00:55:23.930
to depoliticize them or try
to take any characteristic

00:55:23.930 --> 00:55:32.500
that may be affecting
the view of the field.

00:55:32.500 --> 00:55:35.180
For instance Garcia Lorca

00:55:35.180 --> 00:55:41.100
and his sexual orientation
was somehow taken apart

00:55:41.100 --> 00:55:47.090
and not emphasized in the
celebration of Garcia Lorca.

00:55:47.090 --> 00:55:53.710
Finally, a word about--
and just coming to an end,

00:55:53.710 --> 00:55:58.150
a word about the networks.

00:55:58.150 --> 00:56:03.790
Exile opened a Pandora box
of multiple possibilities.

00:56:03.790 --> 00:56:08.400
Again, return is just--
was just one of them.

00:56:08.400 --> 00:56:13.350
That as Ernesto emphasized,
people leaving their countries

00:56:13.350 --> 00:56:18.820
as part of a wave of exile
may remain and many were

00:56:18.820 --> 00:56:23.030
in such position, may
remain attached emotionally,

00:56:23.030 --> 00:56:28.330
intellectually to what is going
on in their country of origin.

00:56:28.330 --> 00:56:32.970
And even if they remained
abroad, many of them try

00:56:32.970 --> 00:56:37.900
to contribute, become members
of networks, academic networks,

00:56:37.900 --> 00:56:41.710
intellectual networks
and political networks,

00:56:41.710 --> 00:56:47.120
and as such they
continue to contribute

00:56:47.120 --> 00:56:49.360
to the opening of
those societies.

00:56:49.360 --> 00:56:55.510
And the major sign of such
opening has been the embracing

00:56:55.510 --> 00:56:58.810
of two characteristic of
modern and Latin America.

00:56:58.810 --> 00:57:03.200
One of them is the rural
discovery of Latin America.

00:57:03.200 --> 00:57:05.750
This is not something new.

00:57:05.750 --> 00:57:09.190
For instance if you
go back in history,

00:57:09.190 --> 00:57:11.230
many of the revolutionaries

00:57:11.230 --> 00:57:15.710
of Latin America were playing
not just with the support

00:57:15.710 --> 00:57:20.410
of their-- of the citizens
of their own country

00:57:20.410 --> 00:57:26.160
but with a wide range of people
coming from all other countries.

00:57:26.160 --> 00:57:28.450
This happened in
Central America.

00:57:28.450 --> 00:57:32.110
For instance, look at
the biography of Sandino

00:57:32.110 --> 00:57:35.380
and who were the
lieutenants of Sandino.

00:57:35.380 --> 00:57:39.980
And this is just one
example of many networks.

00:57:39.980 --> 00:57:44.720
For instance, female
networks of intellectuals,

00:57:44.720 --> 00:57:47.510
those were networks
of people building

00:57:47.510 --> 00:57:51.610
on that transnational
identity which did not deter

00:57:51.610 --> 00:57:55.490
from their support and
commitment to a national sense

00:57:55.490 --> 00:57:59.550
of identity but was
combined and intertwined

00:57:59.550 --> 00:58:01.810
with a national identity.

00:58:01.810 --> 00:58:08.000
And so the rediscovery of Latin
America beyond the national has

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:11.630
been part of this
experience of exile.

00:58:11.630 --> 00:58:22.220
And the second characteristic
is that through the dispersal

00:58:22.220 --> 00:58:26.390
of these networks, some
of the countries have come

00:58:26.390 --> 00:58:30.660
to the conclusion that they
should grant also political

00:58:30.660 --> 00:58:33.920
rights to national [inaudible].

00:58:33.920 --> 00:58:37.560
You can see that in Argentina,

00:58:37.560 --> 00:58:40.860
you can see that in
the case of Paraguay.

00:58:40.860 --> 00:58:46.620
And in the case of Uruguay and
Chile it's more complicated

00:58:46.620 --> 00:58:49.340
but still there have
been attempts

00:58:49.340 --> 00:58:52.990
to launch this connection.

00:58:52.990 --> 00:58:58.550
On the academic field, there is
what we call the [inaudible],

00:58:58.550 --> 00:59:03.930
the drive of those countries
to reconnect with academics,

00:59:03.930 --> 00:59:06.890
with intellectuals,
with people who--

00:59:06.890 --> 00:59:09.890
with professionals
staying abroad.

00:59:09.890 --> 00:59:14.160
And this is an active effort
on the part of those country.

00:59:14.160 --> 00:59:19.650
To sum up, to sum up, exile
has opened those countries

00:59:19.650 --> 00:59:22.990
to globalization, to the
[inaudible] of human rights,

00:59:22.990 --> 00:59:28.110
to rediscovery of Latin American
ties beyond their commitment

00:59:28.110 --> 00:59:32.030
to national identities and
eventually to the possibility

00:59:32.030 --> 00:59:36.930
that to reconsider that
the nation is broader

00:59:36.930 --> 00:59:41.760
than the territory
of a single state.

00:59:41.760 --> 00:59:49.040
Just to finish with one
example of that in the realm

00:59:49.040 --> 00:59:52.810
of literature for Saúl,
[inaudible] after exile,

00:59:52.810 --> 00:59:59.360
during and after exile,
organized a multivolume work

00:59:59.360 --> 01:00:06.310
of critical Argentine-- critical
space of Argentine literature,

01:00:06.310 --> 01:00:09.910
which consider for-- but
it's not the first time

01:00:09.910 --> 01:00:13.580
but which consider in
a proper place the work

01:00:13.580 --> 01:00:17.860
of Argentine writers
writing beyond the territory

01:00:17.860 --> 01:00:20.430
of Argentina.

01:00:20.430 --> 01:00:26.850
For me it has been a--
together with Saúl, with Mario

01:00:26.850 --> 01:00:33.880
and with Leo and exercising
in long running field.

01:00:33.880 --> 01:00:38.080
It's not a short term
but long running.

01:00:38.080 --> 01:00:43.610
Somebody asked me how long have
you been working on this book,

01:00:43.610 --> 01:00:45.490
and I told him, 20 years.

01:00:45.490 --> 01:00:46.880
Oh, 20 years?

01:00:46.880 --> 01:00:52.170
Really? Yes, multiply
five years by four.

01:00:52.170 --> 01:00:53.970
Thank you.

