So I was wondering you guys
talking about the Southern Cone

01:08:58.450 --> 01:09:01.110
and the [inaudible],
transnational ideas,

01:09:01.110 --> 01:09:05.560
if in your research you
talked about Brazil.

01:09:05.560 --> 01:09:09.590
If it has a model
that maybe similar

01:09:09.590 --> 01:09:14.400
to these other Southern Cone
countries or a little different?

01:09:14.400 --> 01:09:15.700
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: OK.

01:09:15.700 --> 01:09:17.700
Very briefly on Brazil
and then Luis can expand.

01:09:17.700 --> 01:09:19.410
We decided at the very
beginning to exclude Brazil

01:09:19.410 --> 01:09:20.770
because it required a different
type of treatment all together.

01:09:20.770 --> 01:09:22.070
And that was the only
reason why we stuck

01:09:22.070 --> 01:09:23.370
to these four countries.

01:09:23.370 --> 01:09:24.670
Although we are all aware of
the fact that the whole wave

01:09:24.670 --> 01:09:25.970
of coup-- coup d'etats
begin with Brazil in 1964,

01:09:25.970 --> 01:09:27.270
that the impact it has had,

01:09:27.270 --> 01:09:28.570
the fact that it also
received exiles from each

01:09:28.570 --> 01:09:29.870
of the other countries.

01:09:29.870 --> 01:09:31.170
But we decided on the
methodological basis

01:09:31.170 --> 01:09:32.470
to leave Brazil out
of this consideration.

01:09:32.470 --> 01:09:33.770
And in terms of what
Gwen was addressing,

01:09:33.770 --> 01:09:35.070
the fact that some
people ended up in exile

01:09:35.070 --> 01:09:36.370
in certain countries sometimes
was just happenstance.

01:09:36.370 --> 01:09:37.670
It just happened.

01:09:37.670 --> 01:09:38.970
And the moment you mentioned
the mechanic in Moscow,

01:09:38.970 --> 01:09:40.270
I was reminded of the case of
[inaudible] who was a Tupamaro

01:09:40.270 --> 01:09:41.570
who spent about a
decade in jail and so on.

01:09:41.570 --> 01:09:42.870
When he got out of jail,
he ended up in Sweden.

01:09:42.870 --> 01:09:44.170
I asked him, why did
you go to Sweden?

01:09:44.170 --> 01:09:45.470
That was the first ticket
that was offered to me.

01:09:45.470 --> 01:09:46.770
And in some cases
that's how it happened.

01:09:46.770 --> 01:09:48.070
&gt;&gt; All right.

01:09:48.070 --> 01:09:49.370
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: So he went
to Sweden, he learned Swedish.

01:09:49.370 --> 01:09:50.670
He published there.

01:09:50.670 --> 01:09:51.970
He had great success
within the Swedish community

01:09:51.970 --> 01:09:53.270
until one day he woke up and he
said, it happens to all of us

01:09:53.270 --> 01:09:54.570
at one point, what
am I doing here?

01:09:54.570 --> 01:09:55.870
And that he's more a literary
and he's also visual artist.

01:09:55.870 --> 01:09:57.170
He was the director of
the National Library

01:09:57.170 --> 01:09:58.470
and several things are very,
very interesting about him

01:09:58.470 --> 01:09:59.770
because he broke with the
Tupamaros while being in jail

01:09:59.770 --> 01:10:01.070
and he decided that was the
wrong approach and so on.

01:10:01.070 --> 01:10:02.370
So I asked him, so
what happened then?

01:10:02.370 --> 01:10:03.670
And his response was
very clear, look at me.

01:10:03.670 --> 01:10:04.970
I interviewed him
when he was a director

01:10:04.970 --> 01:10:06.270
of the National Library.

01:10:06.270 --> 01:10:07.570
Pepe Mujica appointed him to
that point-- to that post.

01:10:07.570 --> 01:10:08.870
So that indicated to the degree

01:10:08.870 --> 01:10:10.170
to which there was a certain
openness, ideological openness,

01:10:10.170 --> 01:10:13.760
political openness, and as well
as experience in practicality

01:10:13.760 --> 01:10:15.990
in terms of how they
related to each other

01:10:15.990 --> 01:10:19.760
within the Tupamaro movement
at least while in jail

01:10:19.760 --> 01:10:21.680
and once they got out.

01:10:21.680 --> 01:10:26.520
But he goes to Sweden because
that's where the ticket was.

01:10:26.520 --> 01:10:27.900
Obviously the case of exiles

01:10:27.900 --> 01:10:29.520
from the communist
party was different.

01:10:29.520 --> 01:10:33.110
Everything was very organized
and they moved in blocks

01:10:33.110 --> 01:10:36.240
to certain countries, to
Eastern Europe and so on.

01:10:36.240 --> 01:10:38.650
So-- but it did vary
quite a bit.

01:10:38.650 --> 01:10:40.600
And then there were the
cases of many people

01:10:40.600 --> 01:10:43.650
who went wherever
they were able to go

01:10:43.650 --> 01:10:47.180
and however they were
able to get to the border.

01:10:47.180 --> 01:10:51.630
So, I don't think we can make
a blanket statement that--

01:10:51.630 --> 01:10:52.930
&gt;&gt; No, it wasn't that--

01:10:52.930 --> 01:10:54.400
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: Yeah, I
know you weren't making that

01:10:54.400 --> 01:10:59.230
but I was-- basically
thinking of the whole process

01:10:59.230 --> 01:11:02.920
of how somebody will end
up in a certain place

01:11:02.920 --> 01:11:06.130
that is not necessarily logical.

01:11:06.130 --> 01:11:08.840
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo: But I do,
I mean emphasize in something

01:11:08.840 --> 01:11:14.610
that you said and the
book describes on my count

01:11:14.610 --> 01:11:18.410
between half a million
and 800,000 exiles.

01:11:18.410 --> 01:11:22.330
And the group of people that
the Insulsas [assumed spelling],

01:11:22.330 --> 01:11:23.770
the Portantieros, you know,

01:11:23.770 --> 01:11:25.900
the ones that were mentioned
are a fraction of those.

01:11:25.900 --> 01:11:28.410
And many of those
that we are talking

01:11:28.410 --> 01:11:31.430
about that are a fraction of
those were already Insulsa

01:11:31.430 --> 01:11:32.740
and Portantiero before leaving.

01:11:32.740 --> 01:11:34.040
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: Absolutely.

01:11:34.040 --> 01:11:35.570
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo: So Portantiero
had created [foreign language].

01:11:35.570 --> 01:11:39.360
Insulsa was on his own right
already an important scholar

01:11:39.360 --> 01:11:41.830
and when he arrived he
forms [inaudible] Mexico.

01:11:41.830 --> 01:11:45.140
Most of them, when they arrive
from exile-- I mean on exile,

01:11:45.140 --> 01:11:47.370
immediately they were
absorbed in the societies.

01:11:47.370 --> 01:11:50.590
They did not train
and-- so that talks

01:11:50.590 --> 01:11:52.540
about social capital
what was there but not

01:11:52.540 --> 01:11:53.860
about the entire million.

01:11:53.860 --> 01:11:56.370
There's a lot of people
that went on exile

01:11:56.370 --> 01:12:02.050
that only face destruction
but not face the other side

01:12:02.050 --> 01:12:04.270
of the book, you know,

01:12:04.270 --> 01:12:08.760
the constructive part,
chapters 5 through.

01:12:08.760 --> 01:12:11.910
And they are in a sense the
ones that only pay the cost

01:12:11.910 --> 01:12:14.370
and have none of the benefits.

01:12:14.370 --> 01:12:17.670
And that is sort of
a different picture.

01:12:17.670 --> 01:12:20.080
But I do think that is
something to commend on,

01:12:20.080 --> 01:12:21.950
on the way which
they build a book

01:12:21.950 --> 01:12:25.350
which is generally that's the
only painting that we have.

01:12:25.350 --> 01:12:27.670
Generally exile is
starting this way.

01:12:27.670 --> 01:12:30.270
I mean if we think of the
contribution of that book not

01:12:30.270 --> 01:12:35.410
as being 20-year-old but being
a roadmap for the next 20 years,

01:12:35.410 --> 01:12:37.570
we can think that,
you know, the refugees

01:12:37.570 --> 01:12:40.320
that we're getting today
from Syria, you know,

01:12:40.320 --> 01:12:42.920
are going to be also
refugees in 20 years.

01:12:42.920 --> 01:12:44.560
You can have an incredible
amount of structure

01:12:44.560 --> 01:12:46.670
on the one hand and
an incredible amount

01:12:46.670 --> 01:12:48.660
of human capital and
political capital that's going

01:12:48.660 --> 01:12:49.960
to be generated.

01:12:49.960 --> 01:12:53.610
And most people are
looking at the human costs

01:12:53.610 --> 01:12:56.150
which are the most
important thing to focus now.

01:12:56.150 --> 01:12:58.780
But it is true that there's
human capital to be built

01:12:58.780 --> 01:13:01.100
and that's also an
important feature

01:13:01.100 --> 01:13:03.340
that I think the
book does bring,

01:13:03.340 --> 01:13:06.100
you know, very forcefully.

01:13:06.100 --> 01:13:08.730
&gt;&gt; Luis Roniger:
Yes, if I may ask--

01:13:08.730 --> 01:13:15.210
add something the label of
exile something sometimes--

01:13:15.210 --> 01:13:18.290
something very Byronic about it.

01:13:18.290 --> 01:13:22.630
That is maybe manipulated
as well.

01:13:22.630 --> 01:13:24.620
We should be aware of that.

01:13:24.620 --> 01:13:28.440
It's not by chance that we
distinguish between the exiles

01:13:28.440 --> 01:13:33.220
of the Southern Cone and the
refugees of Central America.

01:13:33.220 --> 01:13:38.590
Even the words that we use,
color, what we are looking for,

01:13:38.590 --> 01:13:42.170
but we may turn as analyst,

01:13:42.170 --> 01:13:48.310
as people who started
this phenomenon.

01:13:48.310 --> 01:13:52.250
We may turn it being
the word of the danger

01:13:52.250 --> 01:13:55.290
of using these labels,
we may turn it

01:13:55.290 --> 01:13:58.190
into a tool of investigation.

01:13:58.190 --> 01:14:02.890
And this is what I think we have
done because we find differences

01:14:02.890 --> 01:14:07.220
between the different
diasporas in the way even

01:14:07.220 --> 01:14:12.310
in these four cases, in
the way in which the exiles

01:14:12.310 --> 01:14:16.290
within the community
of nationals abroad,

01:14:16.290 --> 01:14:22.510
unless you said-- and those
are not exactly the same.

01:14:22.510 --> 01:14:27.300
Exiles are part of a larger
community of sojourners,

01:14:27.300 --> 01:14:32.780
of diplomats, of
students, of migrants of--

01:14:32.780 --> 01:14:36.160
and all sorts of people
who left their countries

01:14:36.160 --> 01:14:37.740
for different reasons.

01:14:37.740 --> 01:14:42.280
Some for economic motivations,
others for political reasons

01:14:42.280 --> 01:14:47.210
but still there is a core
of exiles and the question

01:14:47.210 --> 01:14:51.660
for research is did
they became the voice

01:14:51.660 --> 01:14:54.390
that represented the community.

01:14:54.390 --> 01:14:59.320
And in some cases we found
that exiles spoke in the name

01:14:59.320 --> 01:15:02.260
of all the people
who are in some way

01:15:02.260 --> 01:15:08.010
or another forced to
leave the country.

01:15:08.010 --> 01:15:12.980
And in other cases,
this was less prominent.

01:15:12.980 --> 01:15:16.310
And so-- And this is
the differentiation

01:15:16.310 --> 01:15:21.780
that we can trace in these
four cases and we trace them

01:15:21.780 --> 01:15:25.680
and it can be also
traced in other cases.

01:15:25.680 --> 01:15:30.670
In about Brazil,
Brazil there is a lot

01:15:30.670 --> 01:15:35.870
of interest today
in Brazilian exile.

01:15:35.870 --> 01:15:40.200
It started unlike of
what you were told.

01:15:40.200 --> 01:15:45.890
It started with a book
in 1999 by a historian.

01:15:45.890 --> 01:15:49.610
You may know her,
Denise Rollemberg.

01:15:49.610 --> 01:15:52.880
The title of her
book is very telling.

01:15:52.880 --> 01:15:57.340
It was called "Entre
Raizes e Radares".

01:15:57.340 --> 01:16:01.490
This looking back and looking
forward and in the middle,

01:16:01.490 --> 01:16:05.180
strength in the middle.

01:16:05.180 --> 01:16:08.390
We did not touch it but
there is a large community

01:16:08.390 --> 01:16:11.730
of people working on
the theme of exile

01:16:11.730 --> 01:16:15.020
and return now in Brazil.

01:16:15.020 --> 01:16:18.280
It came late, relatively late.

01:16:18.280 --> 01:16:23.060
In the period that you
were talking about exile,

01:16:23.060 --> 01:16:26.510
this was the period
of many testimonies,

01:16:26.510 --> 01:16:28.830
many personal stories.

01:16:28.830 --> 01:16:33.270
But it took another, almost
another decade or decade

01:16:33.270 --> 01:16:37.580
and a half to reach the point
of being able to analyze

01:16:37.580 --> 01:16:41.400
from a distance the
phenomenon of massive exile

01:16:41.400 --> 01:16:43.880
and forced displacement.

01:16:43.880 --> 01:16:46.690
OK.

