issue that we touch up on

01:18:27.450 --> 01:18:31.060
and at least we point
to an issue

01:18:31.060 --> 01:18:34.660
that it was quite
significant to address.

01:18:34.660 --> 01:18:36.700
And within all of that, I would

01:18:36.700 --> 01:18:40.140
like to stress although
Luis already has done so,

01:18:40.140 --> 01:18:44.160
is the uniqueness of
the Paraguayan case.

01:18:44.160 --> 01:18:49.470
Yes, it is a different
universe in terms of what it was

01:18:49.470 --> 01:18:53.410
from the very beginning
to how the exile operated,

01:18:53.410 --> 01:18:57.200
to how the Paraguayan
community operated,

01:18:57.200 --> 01:19:01.920
to the fact that their most
important cultural institutions

01:19:01.920 --> 01:19:05.290
were not based in Paraguay
but were based in exile.

01:19:05.290 --> 01:19:11.440
And it is a way of
also marking the impact

01:19:11.440 --> 01:19:15.950
of what the dictatorship
can have in the long term.

01:19:15.950 --> 01:19:18.390
Namely we're talking
about the dictatorship

01:19:18.390 --> 01:19:22.640
that is just a few years to
a dictatorship that lasted

01:19:22.640 --> 01:19:26.860
for decades and therefore had
an impact on the entire country

01:19:26.860 --> 01:19:29.390
that is still being felt today.

01:19:29.390 --> 01:19:32.260
The dictatorship, the basis

01:19:32.260 --> 01:19:36.060
for the dictatorship has not
disappeared and we see it

01:19:36.060 --> 01:19:39.360
in the daily news
coming out of Paraguay.

01:19:39.360 --> 01:19:43.160
The fact that Stroessner's
birthday is still celebrated

01:19:43.160 --> 01:19:46.710
by many, that many still say
[foreign language] referring

01:19:46.710 --> 01:19:50.520
to the fact--

01:19:50.520 --> 01:19:53.470
&gt;&gt; Juan Uriagereka:
Same thing in Spain.

01:19:53.470 --> 01:19:56.180
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski:
-- same as in Spain.

01:19:56.180 --> 01:19:57.480
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo:
Yeah [inaudible].

01:19:57.480 --> 01:19:58.780
&gt;&gt; Luis Roniger: Yes.

01:19:58.780 --> 01:20:00.080
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: Yeah, yeah.

01:20:00.080 --> 01:20:04.190
Namely these are issues that
had-- that have not ended.

01:20:04.190 --> 01:20:07.900
This is a life open channel.

01:20:07.900 --> 01:20:11.380
So this is one of the issues
that we have to keep tackling.

01:20:11.380 --> 01:20:12.680
It's not over.

01:20:12.680 --> 01:20:13.980
&gt;&gt; Luis Roniger: Yeah.

01:20:13.980 --> 01:20:16.530
And it's recreated
every generation.

01:20:16.530 --> 01:20:21.150
For instance, I'm thinking
of Patricio Guzman--

01:20:21.150 --> 01:20:22.450
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: Yeah.

01:20:22.450 --> 01:20:23.750
&gt;&gt; Luis Roniger:
-- as he retained--

01:20:23.750 --> 01:20:25.050
the filmmaker from Chile.

01:20:25.050 --> 01:20:27.820
As he returns from Chile
and shows what he has done

01:20:27.820 --> 01:20:33.200
for all the filming for the
battala for-- batalla for Chile,

01:20:33.200 --> 01:20:38.500
he shows to the new generations
and people are amazed.

01:20:38.500 --> 01:20:40.780
They were not aware at all.

01:20:40.780 --> 01:20:45.690
By the way, Patricio Guzman did
a wonderful film two years ago.

01:20:45.690 --> 01:20:47.100
I don't know if you know it,

01:20:47.100 --> 01:20:50.150
"El Boton de Nacar",
have you seen it?

01:20:50.150 --> 01:20:53.180
"El Boton de Nacar",
highly recommended.

01:20:53.180 --> 01:20:56.180
Showing that the
entire perception

01:20:56.180 --> 01:21:00.180
of Chile being connected
to the land, to territory,

01:21:00.180 --> 01:21:04.740
fighting the Mapuche is
a totally miscarriage

01:21:04.740 --> 01:21:11.100
of the true identity of Chile
should be connected to the sea.

01:21:11.100 --> 01:21:16.600
And the Mapuche were people of
the sea, not necessarily people

01:21:16.600 --> 01:21:20.320
of the land despite their name.

01:21:20.320 --> 01:21:24.180
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski:
Any comments, please.

01:21:26.390 --> 01:21:27.690
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo: Yeah.

01:21:27.690 --> 01:21:28.990
&gt;&gt; Saúl Sosnowski: One, two.

01:21:28.990 --> 01:21:30.290
Yes. Please

01:21:30.290 --> 01:21:34.240
&gt;&gt; My name is [inaudible]
presentation.

01:21:34.240 --> 01:21:38.500
And part of somewhere
the way you talk--

01:21:38.500 --> 01:21:42.500
You are talking like
dictatorship is totally bad,

01:21:42.500 --> 01:21:45.020
democracy is totally good.

01:21:45.020 --> 01:21:50.570
But I don't see how you
explain like people are anti--

01:21:50.570 --> 01:21:56.420
antifascism and then the
people here, they don't like it

01:21:56.420 --> 01:22:01.550
and democracy because they don't
really have their voice heard,

01:22:01.550 --> 01:22:04.640
then another nonvoter
as you can see.

01:22:04.640 --> 01:22:10.400
And then I also don't see
why that our history tell us

01:22:10.400 --> 01:22:13.950
that United Kingdom,
sometimes they explain,

01:22:13.950 --> 01:22:17.140
sometimes there is a
construct such as China,

01:22:17.140 --> 01:22:21.450
sometime you explain-- you have
Manchuria, you have Mongolia,

01:22:21.450 --> 01:22:22.750
you have [inaudible]

01:22:22.750 --> 01:22:24.960
and sometimes you
