01:23:45.060 --> 01:23:47.340
I'm just wondering,
I know Argentina

01:23:47.340 --> 01:23:52.650
like the United States is
a country of immigrants.

01:23:52.650 --> 01:24:01.120
I imagine all your families came
from somewhere else originally

01:24:01.120 --> 01:24:02.830
and I wonder did you think about
that in terms of your discussion

01:24:02.830 --> 01:24:05.130
and how might that have
affected your thoughts on--

01:24:08.940 --> 01:24:10.340
&gt;&gt; Luis Roniger: Yeah, OK.

01:24:10.340 --> 01:24:11.870
I'll start.

01:24:11.870 --> 01:24:18.900
First of all, the questions
that you posed are far ranging

01:24:18.900 --> 01:24:23.760
and certainly very important
from a comparative perspective.

01:24:23.760 --> 01:24:29.960
It's a-- what we have done
is part of a larger canvas

01:24:29.960 --> 01:24:35.870
of human mobility and you
rightly indicated that some

01:24:35.870 --> 01:24:43.190
of that mobility is for interest
to be open to opportunities,

01:24:43.190 --> 01:24:48.990
economic opportunities, for
instance all sorts of ways

01:24:48.990 --> 01:24:53.310
of migration coming to Latin
America or coming to the USA,

01:24:53.310 --> 01:24:57.650
et cetera, et cetera, and also
that the boundaries of states

01:24:57.650 --> 01:25:01.400
in nations can expand or shrink.

01:25:01.400 --> 01:25:05.030
So our contribution is
more modest in the sense

01:25:05.030 --> 01:25:08.730
that we don't address
the entire range

01:25:08.730 --> 01:25:11.880
of phenomena of human mobility.

01:25:11.880 --> 01:25:17.390
We address especially that
part, a part of that universe

01:25:17.390 --> 01:25:22.140
which is connected with forced
mobility or some connection

01:25:22.140 --> 01:25:27.070
between forced mobility
and some kind of prospects

01:25:27.070 --> 01:25:31.160
of a better life, but
especially forced mobility.

01:25:31.160 --> 01:25:34.320
And this has been a
tradition in the societies

01:25:34.320 --> 01:25:39.180
that we have finalized
for a very long time.

01:25:39.180 --> 01:25:41.880
Going back to colonial times,

01:25:41.880 --> 01:25:44.030
they were already the
[foreign language].

01:25:44.030 --> 01:25:49.100
There was an institution of
forcing people to go out.

01:25:49.100 --> 01:25:51.430
Not simply for political
reasons,

01:25:51.430 --> 01:25:53.820
could be for social reasons,

01:25:53.820 --> 01:25:58.190
for affecting the public
decorum, et cetera, et cetera.

01:25:58.190 --> 01:26:00.650
But by the way, you
mentioned China.

01:26:00.650 --> 01:26:04.770
Also in China the region of
Xinjiang [assumed spelling]

01:26:04.770 --> 01:26:08.720
in the western part of
China was used as a place

01:26:08.720 --> 01:26:14.680
of sending people who the
Chinese empire did not want

01:26:14.680 --> 01:26:20.200
to remain because of corruption,
because of other issues.

01:26:20.200 --> 01:26:22.410
There was also exile in China.

01:26:22.410 --> 01:26:23.990
All empires use exile.

01:26:23.990 --> 01:26:28.710
The UK use exile in Australia.

01:26:28.710 --> 01:26:32.780
The Russia used exile
in Siberia.

01:26:32.780 --> 01:26:34.350
China in Xinjiang.

01:26:34.350 --> 01:26:39.620
So there is a longer
history even

01:26:39.620 --> 01:26:43.370
of the narrow phenomenon
of forced exile.

01:26:43.370 --> 01:26:49.970
Our book is about the last
half century, if you wish.

01:26:49.970 --> 01:26:52.070
So it's more restricted.

01:26:52.070 --> 01:26:56.790
It's more modest than the
topics that you suggested

01:26:56.790 --> 01:26:59.100
to cover, but thank you.

01:26:59.100 --> 01:27:08.480
And about certainly in the book
we have a section or subsection

01:27:08.480 --> 01:27:13.880
about Jewish or half
Jewish creators.

01:27:13.880 --> 01:27:21.270
And in that sense we connect
through their work we show

01:27:21.270 --> 01:27:27.180
that this out-migration as
we related to other waves

01:27:27.180 --> 01:27:30.320
of migration crossing
the Atlantic

01:27:30.320 --> 01:27:34.750
in previous generations.

01:27:34.750 --> 01:27:38.940
Also the phenomena of people
trying to flee a country

01:27:38.940 --> 01:27:42.600
in disarray-- in economic
disarray which has been the case

01:27:42.600 --> 01:27:47.690
of Argentina in the early 2000
following the economic crisis.

01:27:47.690 --> 01:27:52.610
Many rediscovered that they were
the descendants of Spaniards,

01:27:52.610 --> 01:27:59.940
of Italians trying to regain the
nationality of their forefathers

01:27:59.940 --> 01:28:05.360
in order to immigrate from
a country in economy crisis.

01:28:05.360 --> 01:28:09.470
So this is-- we-- there are
some sections of the book

01:28:09.470 --> 01:28:11.180
in which we address that.

01:28:11.180 --> 01:28:16.970
Especially interesting for me
is the chapter on the Jewish

01:28:16.970 --> 01:28:22.920
or the subchapter, the
section on the Jewish

01:28:22.920 --> 01:28:28.220
or partly Jewish authors
because they recreate

01:28:28.220 --> 01:28:32.330
through their work the
reminiscence of their--

01:28:32.330 --> 01:28:36.590
the diaspora of their
forefathers.

01:28:36.590 --> 01:28:43.210
This is a-- I'm doing bad
service to the authors

01:28:43.210 --> 01:28:46.740
but it's wonderful to
read how they reflect

01:28:46.740 --> 01:28:50.280
on their own personal
experience in the book.

01:28:50.280 --> 01:28:51.580
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo:
And the book does

01:28:51.580 --> 01:28:53.250
in the beginning
discusses immigration

01:28:53.250 --> 01:28:55.560
in these countries
and not just exile.

01:28:55.560 --> 01:28:56.860
&gt;&gt; Juan Uriagereka: Yes.

01:28:56.860 --> 01:28:58.160
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo:
And in quite detail.

01:28:58.160 --> 01:29:03.550
That said in-- so in
the US and the Latino

01:29:03.550 --> 01:29:05.350
in Argentina exile the--

01:29:05.350 --> 01:29:08.610
in Mexico [inaudible]
so you know the--

01:29:08.610 --> 01:29:10.050
&gt;&gt; Luis Roniger: Yes.

01:29:10.050 --> 01:29:12.220
&gt;&gt; Ernesto Calvo: I came
to the US 20 years ago,

01:29:12.220 --> 01:29:16.930
25 years ago now and
you know nothing of--

01:29:16.930 --> 01:29:18.540
in fact when you introduced me,

01:29:18.540 --> 01:29:21.210
nothing of what defines
my professional career is

01:29:21.210 --> 01:29:25.460
in any way connected to
the fact that I am exilee.

01:29:25.460 --> 01:29:28.770
So we have competed
in identities.

01:29:28.770 --> 01:29:30.450
And on the book I
think it's very clear,

01:29:30.450 --> 01:29:33.880
I'm saying that at some point
being part of exile mutated

01:29:33.880 --> 01:29:35.520
to a lot of very
different things.

01:29:35.520 --> 01:29:39.250
It's very clear by the end that,
you know, what you just said

01:29:39.250 --> 01:29:41.920
about some journey, you know
this journey [inaudible]

01:29:41.920 --> 01:29:44.070
that are taken on
different identities

01:29:44.070 --> 01:29:46.060
and making different
roles and choices.

01:29:46.060 --> 01:29:52.060
So, my grandfather was a
refugee from Lithuania,

01:29:52.060 --> 01:29:55.350
actually from Vilna
and got to Argentina.

01:29:55.350 --> 01:29:59.120
And my great grandmother died in
Auschwitz but I don't consider

01:29:59.120 --> 01:30:02.490
that and he didn't consider
himself as an exilee

01:30:02.490 --> 01:30:04.040
and he moved when we was 15.

01:30:04.040 --> 01:30:07.200
And then my mother moved at 15
to Buenos Aires from [inaudible]

01:30:07.200 --> 01:30:10.880
after the great depression
and then I moved to Argentina

01:30:10.880 --> 01:30:13.740
when I was 15 by myself
because they were in Mexico.

01:30:13.740 --> 01:30:16.100
So we are cut by different
identities but each one

01:30:16.100 --> 01:30:18.110
of those movements were

01:30:18.110 --> 01:30:20.810
in a sense different
identity formation events.

01:30:20.810 --> 01:30:24.470
